WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.560
[Amit Varma]: Regular listeners of the scene and the unseen would have heard me complain about the predatory

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:12.560
[Amit Varma]: parasitic Indian state.

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:14.440
[Amit Varma]: But this is a bit of a simplification.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:18.480
[Amit Varma]: Yes, the Indian state is a parasite, but it is not just one thing.

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:23.380
[Amit Varma]: It is a vast complex machine with many moving parts, and the whole is worse than the sum

00:00:23.380 --> 00:00:24.380
[Amit Varma]: of its parts.

00:00:24.380 --> 00:00:29.040
[Amit Varma]: There are outstanding bureaucrats and well-meaning politicians within the system, but there are

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:32.240
[Amit Varma]: also bad incentives, which lead to bad outcomes.

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:38.520
[Amit Varma]: Also, the Indian state is a multi-headed monster, and some of those heads are often at war with

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:39.520
[Amit Varma]: each other.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:45.280
[Amit Varma]: Consider, for example, the constant tussle between the government and the central bank.

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:49.980
[Amit Varma]: Our imagination feasts on conflict and battle and winners and losers, but it must be said

00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:55.320
[Amit Varma]: that no one is making a Netflix series anytime soon on the life of a central banker.

00:00:55.320 --> 00:01:00.120
[Amit Varma]: Maybe they should.

00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:05.280
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:06.280
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:06.280 --> 00:01:12.200
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:13.200
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:18.520
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Viral Acharya, who was deputy governor of the Reserve Bank of India between

00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:20.760
[Amit Varma]: 2017 and 2019.

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:26.520
[Amit Varma]: Widely respected among economists, Viral quit the RBI six months before his term ended reportedly

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:31.160
[Amit Varma]: because he wasn't happy with the way the government was preventing the RBI from carrying out its

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:32.160
[Amit Varma]: duty.

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:33.160
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, he wasn't happy.

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:38.340
[Amit Varma]: Viral has just released an excellent book called Quest for Restoring Financial Stability

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:43.920
[Amit Varma]: in India, in which he lays out in great detail why we are in the middle of a crisis.

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:47.160
[Amit Varma]: At the core of it is a concept called fiscal dominance.

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:49.880
[Amit Varma]: If I had to sum that up, I'd do it thus.

00:01:49.880 --> 00:01:55.160
[Amit Varma]: Fiscal dominance is a means by which a state thrives at the expense of society using the

00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:57.320
[Amit Varma]: central bank as its tool.

00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:01.120
[Amit Varma]: If you think this is going to be a boring episode about finance, let me assure you,

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:04.320
[Amit Varma]: Viral is anything but a boring, funny, nutty technocrat.

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:05.320
[Amit Varma]: He loves cricket.

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:10.520
[Amit Varma]: He's written and composed a music album called Yadav Ke Silsile and can make economics and

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:16.080
[Amit Varma]: finance quite as lovely and interesting as both cricket and music.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:22.040
[Amit Varma]: Before we begin our conversation though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:25.600
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Scene and the Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:26.880
[Amit Varma]: show alive.

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:29.920
[Amit Varma]: The Scene and the Unseen has been a labor of love for me.

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:35.520
[Amit Varma]: I've enjoyed putting together many stimulating conversations, expanding my brain and my universe,

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:36.520
[Amit Varma]: and hopefully yours as well.

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:41.840
[Amit Varma]: But while the work has been its own reward, I don't actually make much money off the show.

00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:46.280
[Amit Varma]: Although The Scene and the Unseen has great numbers, advertisers haven't really woken up

00:02:46.280 --> 00:02:48.840
[Amit Varma]: to the insane engagement level of podcasts.

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:53.240
[Amit Varma]: And I do many, many hours of deep research for each episode, besides all the logistics

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:59.360
[Amit Varma]: of producing the show myself, scheduling guests, booking studios, paying technicians, the travel

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:00.360
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:04.740
[Amit Varma]: So, well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing going and that involves you.

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:09.280
[Amit Varma]: My proposition for you is this, for every episode of The Scene and the Unseen that you

00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:14.600
[Amit Varma]: enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee or even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel it's worth.

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:20.400
[Amit Varma]: You can do this by heading over to sceneunseen.in slash support and contributing an amount of

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:21.400
[Amit Varma]: your choice.

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:23.480
[Amit Varma]: This is not a subscription.

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:30.520
[Amit Varma]: The Scene and the Unseen will continue to be free on all podcast apps and at sceneunseen.in.

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:33.120
[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:39.440
[Amit Varma]: Help keep this thing going, sceneunseen.in slash support.

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:43.440
[Amit Varma]: Viral, welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:44.440
[Guest]: Thank you, Amit.

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:49.560
[Guest]: I'm delighted to be part of your podcast and I look forward to the interaction.

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:54.720
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we start talking about your book and in a broader sense about India's

00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:58.560
[Amit Varma]: system of governance and our financial system and all of that, tell me a little bit about

00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:03.300
[Amit Varma]: your sort of personal journey, where did you study, what did you do, what were your sort

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:07.720
[Amit Varma]: of intellectual influences that shaped you along the way?

00:04:07.720 --> 00:04:14.600
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, I studied at, we used to live in South Bombay, in Chira Bazar in a street

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:16.440
[Guest]: called Ghazdar Street.

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:25.360
[Guest]: I grew up frankly, like any other street boy, I used to play a lot of gully cricket and

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:33.360
[Guest]: dance all the way with Ganpati from our street to the Chowpatty for Ganpati Visarjan and

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:34.360
[Guest]: all that.

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:40.200
[Guest]: I was in a school, in a Gujarati school, which also had English medium called Fellowship

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:42.000
[Guest]: School.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.200
[Guest]: And the reason why I'm going through a little bit of my school journey is actually that

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:51.840
[Guest]: was probably the most important intellectual part of my journey.

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:59.160
[Guest]: And we were in this very interesting phase of the school where a set of school teachers,

00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:04.160
[Guest]: they decided that our school should also be able to produce students who are in the merit

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:09.920
[Guest]: list of the state for the SSC, the 10th standard exam.

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:16.360
[Guest]: And you know, the school was very balanced culturally, we had actually great music and

00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:22.320
[Guest]: cultural aspect to the school, but on the academic side, I think the teachers were excellent.

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:27.720
[Guest]: But you know, cracking exams and getting into merit list requires a slightly focused kind

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:30.000
[Guest]: of preparation.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.400
[Guest]: And these teachers actually, around the time maybe we were in seventh or eighth grade,

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:40.000
[Guest]: they set this motto for all of us that, you know, this is the challenge, this is the luxury

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.560
[Guest]: that we have to achieve.

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:48.400
[Guest]: And then, you know, it was, they were so motivated, of course, parents in India are always motivated

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:50.800
[Guest]: for their kids to do well.

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:53.520
[Guest]: And then we also got a bit charged up.

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:57.920
[Guest]: And one of the teachers, he passed away two years back, his name is Shailesh Chassar,

00:05:57.920 --> 00:05:59.840
[Guest]: as we used to call him.

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:04.720
[Guest]: And in fact, my book, Quest for Restoring Financial Stability in India is dedicated

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:06.200
[Guest]: to him.

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:10.600
[Guest]: He was the one who kind of really set me on fire, so to speak.

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:17.200
[Guest]: He tutored me as a private coach, so to speak, you know, without charging my parents single

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:19.960
[Guest]: paisa for three years in a row.

00:06:19.960 --> 00:06:26.680
[Guest]: But it was his single-minded focus that in the end created that aspiration, that ambition.

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:32.040
[Guest]: And as I said, whenever I think of him, I think of this, you know, Hrithik Roshan's

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:37.800
[Guest]: song from Lakshya, Lakshya ko har haal mein paana hai, you know, it was that kind of single-minded

00:06:37.800 --> 00:06:38.800
[Guest]: focus.

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:42.920
[Guest]: And, you know, it then sort of all worked out.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:47.000
[Guest]: And you know, I got into Rupert Hill College, which was sort of the college to be in if

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.640
[Guest]: you had done well in SSE that time, I took Electronics.

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:57.680
[Guest]: And then I had a friend in my street just across our building, you know, a lot of people

00:06:57.680 --> 00:07:02.760
[Guest]: you knew in our street more because you could look into their balconies.

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:06.040
[Guest]: And he had been at IIT Mumbai.

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:12.120
[Guest]: And so I spoke to him, then, you know, we got into some correspondence courses, I got

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:13.960
[Guest]: into IIT.

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:20.560
[Guest]: Like everyone who does well in the JEE entrance exam, I also took Computer Science without

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:24.880
[Guest]: thinking whether that's the right field for me or not.

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:31.720
[Guest]: But after that ambitious phase of the school, IIT was, I would say, more of a self-discovery,

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:33.080
[Guest]: self-exploration phase.

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:39.760
[Guest]: I think that was the time I realized that Computer Science wasn't my calling.

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:44.040
[Guest]: I had some aptitude for it, but I wouldn't say a great aptitude for it.

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:50.200
[Guest]: I was still doing okay through sheer persistence and hard work.

00:07:50.200 --> 00:07:54.680
[Guest]: But I really felt that this is not the subject that I'm breathing, I'm not sleeping.

00:07:54.680 --> 00:07:59.320
[Guest]: This is not what I mean is I'm not staying awake because of the problems in Computer

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:02.640
[Guest]: Science.

00:08:02.640 --> 00:08:09.320
[Guest]: And I started exploring a bit and I took a course in International Finance with Professor

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:10.320
[Guest]: Pushpa Trivedi.

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:14.800
[Guest]: It was an elective course in the last year at IIT Bombay.

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:20.720
[Guest]: And I would say Professor Pushpa Trivedi was like my second critical intellectual mentor

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:25.200
[Guest]: in this journey because her course was really the turning point.

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:31.240
[Guest]: It made it clear to me that economics was a subject where you could really bridge the

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:33.720
[Guest]: macro with the micro.

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:41.440
[Guest]: You know, economia is, of course, the study of the household wealth management, even though

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:46.880
[Guest]: most people don't realize it because we use the term economy, etc. so commonly that we

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:49.480
[Guest]: think it has something to do in this grand scheme of things.

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:54.760
[Guest]: But it's really at the grassroots, it's really about the household wealth management.

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:58.560
[Guest]: And the fact that what central banks were doing, what was happening across countries

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:05.000
[Guest]: on trade, etc., ultimately had its bearings in what was happening to the household demand

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:07.400
[Guest]: and consumption at the last mile.

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:12.000
[Guest]: I found that very, very appealing in some ways.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:17.400
[Guest]: And then, you know, again, we had a family friend who had done a PhD in finance at New

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:19.680
[Guest]: York University Stern School of Business.

00:09:19.680 --> 00:09:21.600
[Guest]: I spoke to him.

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:26.280
[Guest]: He said, you know, this is a very interesting subject, it can be very analytical, very mathematical

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:27.280
[Guest]: if you want.

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:31.320
[Guest]: It can be very applied and data oriented if you like.

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:39.360
[Guest]: You can be an academic if you like, or you could be in industry doing trading with stocks,

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:42.560
[Guest]: bonds, derivatives, whatever.

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:46.440
[Guest]: And I said, you know, let's take the plunge and we will see how it goes.

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:51.120
[Guest]: So it was too late by the time I left for my PhD in computer science.

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:58.760
[Guest]: So I did a one year sort of in computer science, but then I switched my major at NYU.

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:04.400
[Guest]: And it was a very interesting phase around 97, 98, when, you know, Southeast Asian crisis

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:09.440
[Guest]: happened, the Russian default happened, the largest hedge fund at that time, long term

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:12.720
[Guest]: capital management was about to fail.

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:18.360
[Guest]: And that was the time I realized that financial stability is actually very, very crucial to

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:25.120
[Guest]: an economy, that if your banks and financial firms are not in great shape, they could become

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:29.080
[Guest]: a source of huge deceleration in the growth of the economy.

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:33.640
[Guest]: And I always think of finance as the lifeblood of the economy.

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:38.500
[Guest]: Sometimes I think of central bank almost like the heart that's regulating the pumping of

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:43.640
[Guest]: these liquidity through various channels into the economy.

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:48.520
[Guest]: And if these banks, which you can sort of think about as, you know, the arteries along

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:54.840
[Guest]: the way, if they are clogged up, then you know, you can have problems in your organs,

00:10:54.840 --> 00:10:58.560
[Guest]: you can have problems all the way to the heart also.

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:05.440
[Guest]: And so it dawned upon me that this is a fascinating aspect of economics and finance.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:07.080
[Guest]: What role do banks play?

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:11.760
[Guest]: What role do other forms of financial sector firms play?

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:13.920
[Guest]: What is the role of the central bank?

00:11:13.920 --> 00:11:20.800
[Guest]: Why is it that when banks and non-bank finance is not in great shape, economic outcomes thereafter

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:25.960
[Guest]: typically don't tend to be very good, as we have seen in India, for instance, over the

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:27.600
[Guest]: last decade.

00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:32.040
[Guest]: So that gave me a direction in economics on my research.

00:11:32.040 --> 00:11:35.800
[Guest]: And I've basically, I would say, stayed with that thought.

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:41.280
[Guest]: That is one thought that keeps crossing my mind over and over and over and over again.

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:48.480
[Guest]: There are so many shades to it that you can analyze, there is so much depth to that question.

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:53.320
[Guest]: And there are so many settings all over the world, because every economy is slightly different.

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:55.760
[Guest]: Every financial sector is slightly different.

00:11:55.760 --> 00:12:01.800
[Guest]: You get different shocks that create these disturbances in a variety of settings.

00:12:01.800 --> 00:12:03.680
[Guest]: So I did my research.

00:12:03.680 --> 00:12:05.720
[Guest]: I went to London Business School.

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:08.680
[Guest]: I then came back to NYU.

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:15.040
[Guest]: You know, around the time I was finishing my PhD, Dr. Raghuram Rajan had just had, I

00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:20.480
[Guest]: would say, his sort of fairly meteoric rise in the economics profession.

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:25.880
[Guest]: He was also studying banking and around that time also banking crises.

00:12:25.880 --> 00:12:31.320
[Guest]: He then went on to become the chief economist of the IMF, the governor of the central bank.

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:36.480
[Guest]: But I think in a way, I would say he was probably the third important mentor, even though he

00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:43.080
[Guest]: has never been my direct mentor, but I worked with him after my PhD, because I was at NYU,

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:44.080
[Guest]: Chicago.

00:12:44.080 --> 00:12:50.520
[Guest]: But I think he has been a mentor more through setting sort of like a role model in the sense

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:57.120
[Guest]: that you know, coming from India, coming from engineering into economics, finance, working

00:12:57.120 --> 00:13:01.840
[Guest]: in the field of banking, etc, that you know, you can make it, you know, it gives you a

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:09.520
[Guest]: little bit of confidence that you can break through these barriers and, you know, have

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:12.680
[Guest]: your own standing, so to speak, in the field.

00:13:12.680 --> 00:13:17.960
[Guest]: And then the field is such the issue of financial stability, bank, central banking, that it's

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:23.280
[Guest]: a natural culmination for many people working in this area, who have a shot at a central

00:13:23.280 --> 00:13:30.680
[Guest]: banking management position, because it allows you to apply your research, it allows you

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:36.360
[Guest]: a little bit to of course, learn things on the job that you can't learn in an academics

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:37.640
[Guest]: armchair.

00:13:37.640 --> 00:13:41.880
[Guest]: And in some small way, I think, you know, give back to society.

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:46.600
[Guest]: And I said, you know, central bankers role is exactly what appealed me about economics

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:47.600
[Guest]: at one level.

00:13:47.600 --> 00:13:52.040
[Guest]: Now, I always give this example, you're just turning this one interest rate dial, you know,

00:13:52.040 --> 00:13:56.080
[Guest]: by 25 basis points, like point 25%.

00:13:56.080 --> 00:13:59.720
[Guest]: And it is supposed to go and touch people in the economy.

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:04.680
[Guest]: Now, at some level, it looks kind of almost like a surreal thought, you know, that is

00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:07.360
[Guest]: this really even possible?

00:14:07.360 --> 00:14:08.360
[Guest]: But it does.

00:14:08.360 --> 00:14:09.640
[Guest]: And sometimes it doesn't work.

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:10.800
[Guest]: And sometimes it does.

00:14:10.800 --> 00:14:17.520
[Guest]: And I think it's very fascinating to understand what are the preconditions, so that sitting

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:23.160
[Guest]: in your macro offices, you can actually have some micro impact on on streets, such as the

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:25.160
[Guest]: street where I grew up.

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:31.880
[Guest]: So yeah, that's been the intellectual journey, I would say, several important teachers and

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:38.420
[Guest]: mentors or role models have been important, I think, the real life experiences of witnessing

00:14:38.420 --> 00:14:44.480
[Guest]: financial crisis in their sort of wolf fury, so to speak, has been also very important

00:14:44.480 --> 00:14:46.480
[Guest]: learning lesson.

00:14:46.480 --> 00:14:50.680
[Guest]: And I think the stint at the Reserve Bank of India was was probably the best thing I

00:14:50.680 --> 00:14:55.480
[Guest]: could have asked for, personally, because I spent time with my parents and lived with

00:14:55.480 --> 00:15:01.360
[Guest]: them for two and a half years, professionally, because it is the closest I've been to executive

00:15:01.360 --> 00:15:04.760
[Guest]: decision making in a policy role.

00:15:04.760 --> 00:15:13.200
[Guest]: And because India is so complex, so interesting as an economy, and it's it really challenges

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:19.720
[Guest]: you to think through hard about what the right frameworks are and how to go about doing things

00:15:19.720 --> 00:15:25.080
[Guest]: in a manner that you have more intended consequences rather than unintended consequences.

00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:28.600
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we proceed with your career, there are many fascinating strands in what

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:32.160
[Amit Varma]: you just said, which I kind of want to tease out and or you know, one of the interesting

00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:36.440
[Amit Varma]: things which struck me when I was, you know, reading up on you is that, you know, economics

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:38.160
[Amit Varma]: is considered a dismal science.

00:15:38.160 --> 00:15:42.400
[Amit Varma]: So most economists also considered fairly boring, straightforward kind of people, though

00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:47.400
[Amit Varma]: I should tell my listeners that when Viral began this podcast, he had a baseball cap

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:49.760
[Amit Varma]: on with his headphone and t shirt.

00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:51.800
[Amit Varma]: But we are not shooting any video.

00:15:51.800 --> 00:15:54.800
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the things that I'm going to ask you about later is, of course, a music

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:59.560
[Amit Varma]: album that you wrote and composed, Yadav Ke Silsile, which I was listening to earlier

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:01.600
[Amit Varma]: today, and also your passion for cricket.

00:16:01.600 --> 00:16:05.040
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you've used a metaphor of cricket a lot when you've been talking about the economy

00:16:05.040 --> 00:16:06.040
[Amit Varma]: in the role of banks.

00:16:06.040 --> 00:16:09.600
[Amit Varma]: And when you were talking about Dr. Rajan, it struck me that, you know, was he such into

00:16:09.600 --> 00:16:10.600
[Amit Varma]: your dravid perhaps?

00:16:10.600 --> 00:16:19.800
[Guest]: Oh, that's a great question. Yeah, see, cricket is because I kind of grew up on the streets

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:20.800
[Guest]: of Mumbai.

00:16:20.800 --> 00:16:26.440
[Guest]: You know, we used to play on this first, we used to play, of course, in our living room

00:16:26.440 --> 00:16:36.920
[Guest]: and hallway, we used to play on the terrace, you know, everyone in India is everything,

00:16:36.920 --> 00:16:44.680
[Guest]: you do whatever the team requires, it was very creative, you know, we used to play on

00:16:44.680 --> 00:16:45.680
[Guest]: the terrace.

00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:50.800
[Guest]: And when the ball used to go down, we used to have this, the kite flying manja and firki.

00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:57.040
[Guest]: So instead of the kite, we had a bag attached to it, and we used to roll the bag down, someone

00:16:57.040 --> 00:17:02.720
[Guest]: would put the ball back in and you know, we would get the manja to get the ball back up.

00:17:02.720 --> 00:17:09.960
[Guest]: Of course, we used to then play gully cricket, so you know, it will be night matches, floodlights

00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:10.960
[Guest]: and all that.

00:17:10.960 --> 00:17:17.160
[Guest]: So, you know, Jitekarwadi, Khetwadi, SK Patiludhia, and you know, all these places we used to

00:17:17.160 --> 00:17:19.240
[Guest]: go with our team.

00:17:19.240 --> 00:17:20.240
[Guest]: It was great fun.

00:17:20.240 --> 00:17:22.520
[Guest]: I think it became sort of part of your DNA.

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:25.960
[Guest]: And of course, you watch cricket so much, you know, when we grew up, there weren't so

00:17:25.960 --> 00:17:32.720
[Guest]: many channels, Darshan probably had like maybe a little bit of Chitrahaar and then maybe

00:17:32.720 --> 00:17:36.440
[Guest]: the Saturday Marathi movie and the Sunday Hindi movie.

00:17:36.440 --> 00:17:42.320
[Guest]: So you know, cricket, watching cricket and test matches was a very big part of the whole

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:44.360
[Guest]: sort of your pastime.

00:17:44.360 --> 00:17:50.880
[Guest]: So I partly like to use the cricket analogies, besides them coming naturally to me is because

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:53.960
[Guest]: I think that's a way to connect to the common man.

00:17:53.960 --> 00:17:56.840
[Guest]: And to me, that's very, very important.

00:17:56.840 --> 00:18:05.760
[Guest]: Sometimes a few of the speeches I've given are so bare bones, that people in academia

00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:11.640
[Guest]: sometimes feel when I gave these talks that, you know, does it really have to be so basic?

00:18:11.640 --> 00:18:12.640
[Amit Varma]: Does it really?

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:16.720
[Guest]: And my sense is, it's a question of what your audience is, and are you connecting with the

00:18:16.720 --> 00:18:17.720
[Guest]: audience or not?

00:18:17.720 --> 00:18:25.680
[Guest]: You can't, there is no point using jargon and fancy terms and methods and techniques

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:30.760
[Guest]: when you know, you have to convey something much simpler to the common man.

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:36.880
[Guest]: But importantly, I think these being able to connect is equally important with people

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:38.520
[Guest]: at the top in mind.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:46.520
[Guest]: I think even those who are doing very complex policy roles, they actually prefer when things

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:49.600
[Guest]: are explained in a very simple and transparent manner.

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:55.060
[Guest]: And I think that's why, you know, no analogy is perfect, but they work because when people

00:18:55.060 --> 00:18:59.720
[Guest]: see it in a different light, when they can relate to it, they also start feeling that

00:18:59.720 --> 00:19:04.320
[Guest]: maybe there is something like a common thread of a principle here, you know, they start

00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:08.360
[Guest]: seeing that, oh, this is not about a very specific suggestion, maybe there is something

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:12.760
[Guest]: deeper that permeates across different disciplines of life.

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:17.480
[Guest]: So that's the reason why I would say I use the cricket analogy.

00:19:17.480 --> 00:19:21.000
[Guest]: I think the Dravid analogy is one that's very close to my heart.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:25.520
[Guest]: It's actually linked to a question that a good friend of mine from IIT Bombay asked

00:19:25.520 --> 00:19:32.080
[Guest]: me just before, they had given me a send off before I went to Reserve Bank of India.

00:19:32.080 --> 00:19:38.880
[Guest]: So we met at one restaurant outside our place in Manhattan called Heroes, it's a Greek food

00:19:38.880 --> 00:19:39.880
[Guest]: place.

00:19:39.880 --> 00:19:44.760
[Guest]: And I distinctly remember about 10 of them had come down and we sat together and one

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:51.520
[Guest]: of them, my very good friend, he asked me, so who would be your role model as a central

00:19:51.520 --> 00:19:52.520
[Guest]: banker?

00:19:52.520 --> 00:19:54.080
[Guest]: Is it Ben Bernanke?

00:19:54.080 --> 00:19:55.560
[Guest]: Is it Paul Walker?

00:19:55.560 --> 00:19:56.560
[Guest]: Is it Janet Yellen?

00:19:56.560 --> 00:20:00.720
[Guest]: And I said, no, it's going to be Rahul Dravid.

00:20:00.720 --> 00:20:08.800
[Guest]: And I really genuinely mean it because I always thought he was the pillar of the Indian batting

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:14.200
[Guest]: order during his time, the rock bed, sheet anchor, whatever term you want to use.

00:20:14.200 --> 00:20:18.320
[Guest]: There were so many test matches I remember watching where, you know, the entire team

00:20:18.320 --> 00:20:19.600
[Guest]: would bat around him.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:25.080
[Guest]: And because I think of the central bank as a little bit of this heart that is regulating

00:20:25.080 --> 00:20:32.960
[Guest]: all this pushing of lifeblood to the economy, I think that that is the role that is best

00:20:32.960 --> 00:20:36.080
[Guest]: captured, I think, in cricket by Rahul Dravid.

00:20:36.080 --> 00:20:41.080
[Guest]: In fact, and, you know, I think, as I said, financial stability is very important.

00:20:41.080 --> 00:20:48.560
[Guest]: I think it's most important that you need someone with that persistence, with that discipline

00:20:48.560 --> 00:20:55.480
[Guest]: and with that single minded focus of holding the guard when, you know, the situation is

00:20:55.480 --> 00:20:56.480
[Guest]: looking tricky.

00:20:56.480 --> 00:21:01.320
[Guest]: You know, when some of the arteries, some of the banks are blocked, not doing very well.

00:21:01.320 --> 00:21:06.640
[Guest]: In fact, if you remember, in one of his last series in England, which we lost, I think

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:07.640
[Guest]: 3-0.

00:21:07.640 --> 00:21:13.440
[Guest]: No, he scored three centuries because he was the only one holding up one end and giving

00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:18.160
[Guest]: some hope that we might actually at least come out with a draw.

00:21:18.160 --> 00:21:20.000
[Guest]: So I think that's very important.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:23.920
[Guest]: I think, you know, and it's everything, you know, taking the stance, knowing where your

00:21:23.920 --> 00:21:27.120
[Guest]: off stump is, leaving a lot of balls outside the off stump.

00:21:27.120 --> 00:21:30.240
[Guest]: I think this is what the central bank has to do most of the time.

00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:32.840
[Guest]: I think there's a lot of bad ideas.

00:21:32.840 --> 00:21:37.200
[Guest]: I can't tell you how bad some of the ideas are in policymaking.

00:21:37.200 --> 00:21:41.920
[Guest]: Somehow there is this one feature that because economics is so rooted everywhere in each

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:47.760
[Guest]: household's policymaking, and of course, the households are making sometimes the most interesting

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:48.760
[Guest]: decisions.

00:21:48.760 --> 00:21:55.160
[Guest]: There is also this perception, though, that we don't need to acquire any expertise in

00:21:55.160 --> 00:21:56.840
[Guest]: this field.

00:21:56.840 --> 00:22:01.840
[Guest]: Everyone can just go walk into these policy roles and start doing things.

00:22:01.840 --> 00:22:06.320
[Guest]: Now, of course, there will be some talented people who are so smart by their training

00:22:06.320 --> 00:22:08.480
[Guest]: on the ground that they can do it.

00:22:08.480 --> 00:22:14.560
[Guest]: But you know, however imperfect and however young as a field, you know, economics is not

00:22:14.560 --> 00:22:17.800
[Guest]: even 100 years old in some sense as a discipline.

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:21.640
[Guest]: So it's a relatively young field, but however young and imperfect it might be, it is still

00:22:21.640 --> 00:22:22.640
[Guest]: a field.

00:22:22.640 --> 00:22:28.440
[Guest]: And there are some principles and ideas that seem to show up in different countries in

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:33.120
[Guest]: different conditions on a very regular and robust basis.

00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:37.640
[Guest]: And so a big part of the central banking is just not dealing with bad ideas.

00:22:37.640 --> 00:22:40.560
[Guest]: It's these balls which are outside the off stump.

00:22:40.560 --> 00:22:43.920
[Guest]: So I think that's the sort of Rahul Dravid part of it.

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:50.120
[Guest]: Yeah, I think Raghuram Rajan in some ways, I think you could, you could be, you are right.

00:22:50.120 --> 00:22:55.800
[Guest]: I think he could be Tendulkar, but my sense is he's also probably taken a fairly long

00:22:55.800 --> 00:23:02.080
[Guest]: term view, I think, during his time as central banking, you know, moves such as the beginning

00:23:02.080 --> 00:23:10.360
[Guest]: the steps towards inflation targeting framework in India, then, you know, creating a differentiated

00:23:10.360 --> 00:23:14.400
[Guest]: banking system, opening up bank licenses.

00:23:14.400 --> 00:23:19.640
[Guest]: And third, you know, creating this database Krillic as a repository for information on

00:23:19.640 --> 00:23:20.640
[Guest]: large corporates.

00:23:20.640 --> 00:23:24.240
[Guest]: I think all of these were fairly long term moves, actually.

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:28.600
[Guest]: So I would say by and large, you know, to use another example, maybe he's like Rahul

00:23:28.600 --> 00:23:33.440
[Guest]: Dravid, but he also has Virat Kohli's aggression at times.

00:23:33.440 --> 00:23:37.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'm also a big fan of Dravid, of course, and you're absolutely right.

00:23:37.960 --> 00:23:42.840
[Amit Varma]: If you look at all of India's important test wins overseas in that particular decade, you

00:23:42.840 --> 00:23:46.840
[Amit Varma]: know, Headingley, Adelaide, Rawalpindi, the series we won in the Western days, Dravid

00:23:46.840 --> 00:23:49.080
[Amit Varma]: was completely at the heart of it.

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:50.400
[Amit Varma]: I'd save the question for later.

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:54.960
[Amit Varma]: But since you, you know, brought up that subject, I'll kind of ask it now, which is you spoke

00:23:54.960 --> 00:24:00.520
[Amit Varma]: about the importance of, you know, communicating ideas and sort of keeping it simple.

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:04.160
[Amit Varma]: And I, you know, I teach an online writing course, where sometimes students will ask

00:24:04.160 --> 00:24:09.280
[Amit Varma]: me that, listen, you know, I do academic writing, and people in academics expect the kind of

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:13.000
[Amit Varma]: a certain kind of jargon and a certain kind of signaling and all of that.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:17.320
[Amit Varma]: And my response to all of that is that in any context, clear writing is a good thing.

00:24:17.320 --> 00:24:21.760
[Amit Varma]: I can understand that sometimes there are those imperatives where people will expect

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:26.480
[Amit Varma]: you to use language that puts them in their comfort zone, but as clear as possible is

00:24:26.480 --> 00:24:27.480
[Amit Varma]: always a good thing.

00:24:27.480 --> 00:24:31.320
[Amit Varma]: And the imperative of, you know, writing clearly makes you think more clearly, because if you're

00:24:31.320 --> 00:24:35.320
[Amit Varma]: stating something in simpler language, as you do throughout in your book, then you're

00:24:35.320 --> 00:24:37.240
[Amit Varma]: forced to put that kind of thought into it.

00:24:37.240 --> 00:24:41.360
[Amit Varma]: But my broader question, which I wanted to come to was that, you know, when you wrote

00:24:41.360 --> 00:24:45.520
[Amit Varma]: this book, one of the reasons that you said for writing this book was that you wanted

00:24:45.520 --> 00:24:50.520
[Amit Varma]: to start a debate that you felt very deeply that these issues which you're talking about

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:55.600
[Amit Varma]: financial stability, fiscal dominance, they are of great importance, they should not only

00:24:55.600 --> 00:25:01.560
[Amit Varma]: be debated by policy people, the public at large should understand them and sort of talk

00:25:01.560 --> 00:25:03.660
[Amit Varma]: about them, which is an incredible aim.

00:25:03.660 --> 00:25:06.800
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, it struck me, and this is something that, you know, people who write

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:11.880
[Amit Varma]: about economics have been saying forever, that, you know, a lot of the fundamental ideas

00:25:11.880 --> 00:25:17.000
[Amit Varma]: of economics are deeply counterintuitive, you know, spontaneous order, positive, some

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.120
[Amit Varma]: game, how complex systems work.

00:25:19.120 --> 00:25:24.640
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, you know, there is both bounded rationality, which and what public choice

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:29.080
[Amit Varma]: there is called rational ignorance, that for a common person to put in the effort to understand

00:25:29.080 --> 00:25:34.920
[Amit Varma]: the economy, as it were, it's probably just too much of an effort, it's much easier to

00:25:34.920 --> 00:25:38.360
[Amit Varma]: pick a political side, which everybody more or less has.

00:25:38.360 --> 00:25:41.920
[Amit Varma]: And then you go with whatever that side is doing, you defend what they're doing.

00:25:41.920 --> 00:25:45.560
[Amit Varma]: And if you're not with them, then you attack what they're doing, which is how most of our

00:25:45.560 --> 00:25:47.480
[Amit Varma]: public discourse is today.

00:25:47.480 --> 00:25:50.640
[Amit Varma]: So how did you approach that challenge?

00:25:50.640 --> 00:25:56.360
[Amit Varma]: Because these are not easy ideas to sort of, you know, grasp for, you know, a lay person.

00:25:56.360 --> 00:26:00.120
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what were the thoughts that I mean, you've used cricketing analogies and

00:26:00.120 --> 00:26:03.560
[Amit Varma]: all that, and that's worked beautifully and so on.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:05.560
[Amit Varma]: But is that something you consciously thought about that?

00:26:05.560 --> 00:26:07.080
[Amit Varma]: How can I communicate this?

00:26:07.080 --> 00:26:09.200
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely.

00:26:09.200 --> 00:26:16.520
[Guest]: And see, the important thing to realize in policymaking is that, see, over certain functions,

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:21.800
[Guest]: the central bank probably is given legislative autonomy.

00:26:21.800 --> 00:26:27.960
[Guest]: So what I mean is that, think about the inflation targeting framework, it is actually by an

00:26:27.960 --> 00:26:33.840
[Guest]: act of law as an amendment to the Reserve Bank of India Act, that the central bank through

00:26:33.840 --> 00:26:38.640
[Guest]: this Monetary Policy Committee can set the interest rate, this is the objective function

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:40.520
[Guest]: and so on.

00:26:40.520 --> 00:26:46.680
[Guest]: But in many other functions of the central bank, the operational autonomy is very loosely

00:26:46.680 --> 00:26:47.680
[Guest]: defined.

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:53.120
[Guest]: A lot of the decisions, especially in India, as I explain in the book, given the presence

00:26:53.120 --> 00:27:00.360
[Guest]: of public sector banks and other public sector financial institutions, are very often taken

00:27:00.360 --> 00:27:06.760
[Guest]: either jointly with the government through some discussion, conversation, consensus.

00:27:06.760 --> 00:27:11.800
[Guest]: Or if the central bank has to even take certain decisions, the government has to empower the

00:27:11.800 --> 00:27:15.080
[Guest]: central bank through some legislative changes.

00:27:15.080 --> 00:27:18.160
[Guest]: Now, why am I saying all this?

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:25.740
[Guest]: What I'm trying to convey is that for many good policy decisions to be taken, politics

00:27:25.740 --> 00:27:28.600
[Guest]: has to be aligned with the economics.

00:27:28.600 --> 00:27:36.520
[Guest]: The government has to want what makes sense in the long run for the economy as a whole.

00:27:36.520 --> 00:27:44.000
[Guest]: Now, a fundamental thesis of my work, the book, as well as the Rahul Dravid analogy

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:49.320
[Guest]: is that there are pressures sometimes to actually not play the long test match.

00:27:49.320 --> 00:27:55.580
[Guest]: There are pressures to instead play T20, you know, to go and entertain the crowds instead

00:27:55.580 --> 00:28:00.560
[Guest]: of actually winning session by session through endurance.

00:28:00.560 --> 00:28:06.640
[Guest]: And because the political decision making can often be very geared by the short term

00:28:06.640 --> 00:28:13.920
[Guest]: consideration and you put it exactly right, why is it that short term growth will actually

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:16.520
[Guest]: give them political gains?

00:28:16.520 --> 00:28:23.040
[Guest]: It's because the average person on the street may not be able to figure out that the short

00:28:23.040 --> 00:28:28.520
[Guest]: term boost in activity, either because they are getting a lot of credit, or the government

00:28:28.520 --> 00:28:35.140
[Guest]: is distributing a lot of cash through a variety of schemes, that that short term activity

00:28:35.140 --> 00:28:41.240
[Guest]: is down the line, at some future point of time in three or five years time, going to

00:28:41.240 --> 00:28:46.600
[Guest]: come back with a lot of costs because maybe the loans that were made were made without

00:28:46.600 --> 00:28:52.120
[Guest]: due diligence, or the cash that has been distributed is going to be very hard to repay down the

00:28:52.120 --> 00:28:53.120
[Guest]: line.

00:28:53.120 --> 00:29:00.080
[Guest]: Now, so sometimes in the common man, both because of them having to work so hard on

00:29:00.080 --> 00:29:09.040
[Guest]: their own economics, and perhaps because of limits to information processing and rational

00:29:09.040 --> 00:29:14.880
[Guest]: evaluation of data and you know, I think the counterfactuals, what if that is the key question

00:29:14.880 --> 00:29:19.160
[Guest]: that you have to ask in policymaking, what if this were to happen?

00:29:19.160 --> 00:29:23.200
[Guest]: Those things are not always very easy for the common man to perceive.

00:29:23.200 --> 00:29:28.480
[Guest]: And if they can't, in a way that creates the opportunity for the short termism to actually

00:29:28.480 --> 00:29:33.920
[Guest]: lead to gains, that if I do this pump priming of the economy, it can actually lead to some

00:29:33.920 --> 00:29:37.080
[Guest]: benefits during the electoral cycle.

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:43.280
[Guest]: Now, if that is not in the long run interest of the economy, in my view, those who can

00:29:43.280 --> 00:29:52.000
[Guest]: actually perceive what the impact of these short term pump priming of the economy is,

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:57.920
[Guest]: those who are in the job, such as at a central bank, where your objectives are enshrined

00:29:57.920 --> 00:30:04.320
[Guest]: in the law to be long term protecting depositor interest, keeping price stability, guarding

00:30:04.320 --> 00:30:06.760
[Guest]: the value of the rupee, etc.

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:11.640
[Guest]: All of these require sometimes making short term sacrifices, so that you know, you keep

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:14.920
[Guest]: the ship afloat and in good condition.

00:30:14.920 --> 00:30:22.820
[Guest]: So I think it is the responsibility in my view of the central banker to actually use

00:30:22.820 --> 00:30:28.880
[Guest]: communication as one of the tools to advance the public discussion.

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:31.200
[Guest]: And therefore, I think it has to go to the common man as well.

00:30:31.200 --> 00:30:37.200
[Guest]: I think it's not good enough that it reaches the circles of finance industry, bankers,

00:30:37.200 --> 00:30:38.920
[Guest]: market participants.

00:30:38.920 --> 00:30:44.420
[Guest]: You have to try and get it into mainstream media as much as possible.

00:30:44.420 --> 00:30:50.760
[Guest]: And I think the reason is that once you shift the public debate, once you create a demand

00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:57.640
[Guest]: for the right long term reforms in people themselves, then the politics and economics,

00:30:57.640 --> 00:30:59.400
[Guest]: there's a greater chance that you will align.

00:30:59.400 --> 00:31:04.320
[Guest]: See, sometimes politics aligns with economics because, you know, there may be a situation

00:31:04.320 --> 00:31:08.920
[Guest]: where the government has no choice, but to do the right thing for the long run, because

00:31:08.920 --> 00:31:13.960
[Guest]: otherwise, investors will not give you money, like think of 1991 liberalization moment,

00:31:13.960 --> 00:31:19.400
[Guest]: it was a moment where structural changes to the Indian economy were thrust upon us by

00:31:19.400 --> 00:31:23.200
[Guest]: the IMF, because we needed their support, and there was no other way out.

00:31:23.200 --> 00:31:24.840
[Guest]: So that's one way to go.

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:28.160
[Guest]: But you know, reforms do happen all the time.

00:31:28.160 --> 00:31:31.360
[Guest]: Sometimes they happen promptly, sometimes they happen with delay.

00:31:31.360 --> 00:31:36.520
[Guest]: And why do we get these moments where the political consensus arises to undertake these

00:31:36.520 --> 00:31:37.520
[Guest]: reforms?

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:44.520
[Guest]: Very often, I think it's because there is a demand for reforms in the common man's mind,

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:50.560
[Guest]: in the common man's perception, in media, on television, in print media, now in podcast,

00:31:50.560 --> 00:31:52.280
[Guest]: Twitter, whatever it is.

00:31:52.280 --> 00:31:59.760
[Guest]: But you sometimes get this good ideas being planted, seeded, and then they're sort of

00:31:59.760 --> 00:32:04.640
[Guest]: germinating and rising to the top of an agenda.

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:11.160
[Guest]: And as long as there's a critical mass of discussion around the right ideas, I think

00:32:11.160 --> 00:32:14.880
[Guest]: there's a greater chance that the politics and economics will align.

00:32:14.880 --> 00:32:19.160
[Guest]: I think we need to create more such opportunities.

00:32:19.160 --> 00:32:21.880
[Guest]: And to do that, we can't just wait and watch.

00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:27.280
[Guest]: I think we have to plant these seeds of ideas, very often, the ideas germinate, and they

00:32:27.280 --> 00:32:28.880
[Guest]: are not even associated with you.

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:30.320
[Guest]: And I think that's perfectly all right.

00:32:30.320 --> 00:32:34.440
[Guest]: I think you are just trying to get people to debate because very often the person who

00:32:34.440 --> 00:32:39.720
[Guest]: comes up with the original idea and plants the seed may not have the right solution.

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:46.280
[Guest]: Maybe he or she doesn't actually appreciate all the realities of the political economy.

00:32:46.280 --> 00:32:51.320
[Guest]: But once the idea is debated, maybe a better solution emerges.

00:32:51.320 --> 00:32:54.120
[Guest]: But to me, this is absolutely crucial.

00:32:54.120 --> 00:32:59.920
[Guest]: Policymakers have to communicate, they have to communicate with the common man, besides

00:32:59.920 --> 00:33:05.240
[Guest]: the more sophisticated parts in their relevant sphere of influence.

00:33:05.240 --> 00:33:07.160
[Guest]: And I think this is the way change comes about.

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:11.760
[Guest]: So I think to cut a long story short, I think Amit, what I'm trying to say is that while

00:33:11.760 --> 00:33:18.560
[Guest]: it's true that there is bounded rationality, there is limited processing of information.

00:33:18.560 --> 00:33:24.520
[Guest]: And of course, decision making is very concentrated, but we have to build a bridge between these

00:33:24.520 --> 00:33:25.520
[Guest]: two.

00:33:25.520 --> 00:33:32.920
[Guest]: We have to get people to come a bit closer to the decision makers in terms of their discussions

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:33.920
[Guest]: and debates.

00:33:33.920 --> 00:33:39.760
[Guest]: We have to get the decision makers closer to the common man by alerting them about the

00:33:39.760 --> 00:33:45.240
[Guest]: long run consequences of some of the policies and why some things make sense and others

00:33:45.240 --> 00:33:46.240
[Guest]: don't.

00:33:46.240 --> 00:33:48.040
[Guest]: And I think how do you bring them together?

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:54.080
[Guest]: I think your communication is one of the kind of almost, it's a negotiating tool, actually.

00:33:54.080 --> 00:33:59.840
[Guest]: You're bringing these two parties, which often seem far apart, together through public debate

00:33:59.840 --> 00:34:00.840
[Guest]: and discussion.

00:34:00.840 --> 00:34:01.840
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:03.320
[Guest]: I think this is a very crucial role.

00:34:03.320 --> 00:34:07.200
[Guest]: And I think I'm seeing this also in the modern day central bankers.

00:34:07.200 --> 00:34:14.400
[Guest]: I'm not on social media myself as a policy, but I can see that many central bankers are

00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:21.480
[Guest]: now actually using even social media to have an outreach of their ideas.

00:34:21.480 --> 00:34:27.920
[Guest]: Many central banks are now actually, quote unquote, organizing panels and sessions at

00:34:27.920 --> 00:34:33.240
[Guest]: industry events or academic conferences because they want actually to be part of the broader

00:34:33.240 --> 00:34:34.240
[Guest]: discussion and debate.

00:34:34.240 --> 00:34:39.440
[Guest]: So I think over three to four decades, we seem to have moved away from a very boring,

00:34:39.440 --> 00:34:46.920
[Guest]: quiet central banker to a somewhat, I wouldn't necessarily say outspoken always, but sometimes

00:34:46.920 --> 00:34:48.040
[Guest]: even outspoken.

00:34:48.040 --> 00:34:55.280
[Guest]: But certainly, I would say communicative and interactive central banker who's using communication

00:34:55.280 --> 00:35:00.720
[Guest]: as a very, very important tool, both for this negotiation function, as I mentioned, between

00:35:00.720 --> 00:35:04.040
[Guest]: politics, common man and economics.

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:09.600
[Guest]: And I think also to actually explain what they are doing, because that gives them a

00:35:09.600 --> 00:35:14.600
[Guest]: democratic accountability of their actions, you know, because in many cases, central bankers

00:35:14.600 --> 00:35:15.600
[Guest]: are technocrats.

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:18.640
[Guest]: They are taking very technical decisions.

00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:25.280
[Guest]: As I said, what is this changing of this dial of 25 basis points or 0.25% of interest rates.

00:35:25.280 --> 00:35:29.560
[Guest]: But if you can communicate and explain this well to the common man, that increases your

00:35:29.560 --> 00:35:33.960
[Guest]: democratic accountability from the technocratic decisions that you are taking.

00:35:33.960 --> 00:35:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, the challenge of doing that is something that I've been, you know, discussing

00:35:37.640 --> 00:35:41.440
[Amit Varma]: with friends for ages now, because a lot of my friends work in the policy sphere, where

00:35:41.440 --> 00:35:44.600
[Amit Varma]: they'll work with politicians and bureaucrats and try to sell policies.

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:49.560
[Amit Varma]: And my point to them always has been that, you know, if you think of the political marketplace,

00:35:49.560 --> 00:35:53.720
[Amit Varma]: you have to focus on the demand and not the supply and that politicians will respond to

00:35:53.720 --> 00:35:54.720
[Amit Varma]: incentives.

00:35:54.720 --> 00:35:59.480
[Amit Varma]: So if you can change the demand, and then you have people who demand something different,

00:35:59.480 --> 00:36:02.160
[Amit Varma]: then you're far more likely to get those sort of outcomes.

00:36:02.160 --> 00:36:06.200
[Amit Varma]: And you know, again, Andrew Breitbart once said politics is downstream of culture, which

00:36:06.200 --> 00:36:11.000
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, again, that whole act of changing the culture, seeding these ideas, like you

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.280
[Amit Varma]: pointed out is a decades long game.

00:36:13.280 --> 00:36:16.360
[Amit Varma]: You saw it in America with, you know, Goldwater losing in 64.

00:36:16.360 --> 00:36:21.720
[Amit Varma]: And then Reagan coming to power in 80, it takes many, many sort of years to play out.

00:36:21.720 --> 00:36:25.960
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to you know, the specifics of the Indian economy and your time in the Reserve

00:36:25.960 --> 00:36:30.360
[Amit Varma]: Bank of India, I'd also like to just for a moment, get some more background on where

00:36:30.360 --> 00:36:31.360
[Amit Varma]: you're sort of coming from.

00:36:31.360 --> 00:36:35.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we are essentially the same age, I think I'm a couple of months older than you.

00:36:35.920 --> 00:36:39.760
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, this was a question that first struck me when I read about your journey,

00:36:39.760 --> 00:36:44.240
[Amit Varma]: that I kind of spent a certain part of my childhood in pre liberalization, India.

00:36:44.240 --> 00:36:46.920
[Amit Varma]: And then my adulthood is in liberalization, India.

00:36:46.920 --> 00:36:48.580
[Amit Varma]: And it so happened, my dad was in the IAS.

00:36:48.580 --> 00:36:54.000
[Amit Varma]: So I was, of course, steeped in the received wisdom of that Fabian socialist era, where

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:55.240
[Amit Varma]: your state is your my bop.

00:36:55.240 --> 00:36:57.040
[Amit Varma]: And that's where you look at the economy.

00:36:57.040 --> 00:37:01.160
[Amit Varma]: And then you're an adult and sort of the blinkers fall off one by one and you see everything

00:37:01.160 --> 00:37:04.240
[Amit Varma]: kind of differently.

00:37:04.240 --> 00:37:08.920
[Amit Varma]: What was your sort of intellectual evolution through that period like?

00:37:08.920 --> 00:37:13.320
[Amit Varma]: What you know, did your notion of your country and what we were doing right and what we were

00:37:13.320 --> 00:37:14.320
[Amit Varma]: doing wrong?

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:19.480
[Amit Varma]: Did your idea of India, as it were, you know, evolve during that period, especially for

00:37:19.480 --> 00:37:24.040
[Amit Varma]: example, when you went abroad, it must have given you that distance where, you know, you

00:37:24.040 --> 00:37:29.280
[Amit Varma]: can be a little more objective about it, you can contrast it with what you see around you.

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:35.720
[Amit Varma]: Take me a bit through your sort of mindset and your idea of India as it were how it evolved

00:37:35.720 --> 00:37:36.720
[Guest]: in that period.

00:37:36.720 --> 00:37:37.720
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:37:37.720 --> 00:37:45.240
[Guest]: So, I think, you know, as a child, maybe even in my school, college, perhaps even IIT days,

00:37:45.240 --> 00:37:52.400
[Guest]: I wasn't so clear about what exactly India was relative to the rest of the world with

00:37:52.400 --> 00:37:53.400
[Guest]: great clarity.

00:37:53.400 --> 00:38:02.240
[Guest]: Of course, what was very hard not to notice was the fact that it seemed very heavily controlled

00:38:02.240 --> 00:38:09.360
[Guest]: and administered economy certainly until the early 90s.

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:14.200
[Guest]: It seemed like everyone had very few career choices.

00:38:14.200 --> 00:38:19.960
[Guest]: So there clearly weren't too many thriving industries in the country.

00:38:19.960 --> 00:38:29.800
[Guest]: And you knew from all the, you know, the great demand for imported goods, smuggled or otherwise,

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:34.560
[Guest]: that people in the rest of the world were producing goods that were far better than

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:37.240
[Guest]: were produced in India.

00:38:37.240 --> 00:38:43.600
[Guest]: And so, you kind of knew something at the back of your mind that, you know, that something

00:38:43.600 --> 00:38:48.520
[Guest]: is not happening right, though you can't kind of put your finger on it yet, you know, that

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:53.520
[Guest]: why is everyone wanting everything that's produced abroad?

00:38:53.520 --> 00:39:01.360
[Guest]: And then I think when I first came to the United States, I saw the extent of variety

00:39:01.360 --> 00:39:10.760
[Guest]: of produce of various types, the efficiency of customer service on the ground, the sheer

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:14.320
[Guest]: buzz and activity in the economy, etc.

00:39:14.320 --> 00:39:21.280
[Guest]: I kind of realized that this is a very different manner in which the economy is organized.

00:39:21.280 --> 00:39:26.600
[Guest]: And then you suddenly started realizing that at a deeper level, all countries are somewhere

00:39:26.600 --> 00:39:34.240
[Guest]: on a continuum of, you know, sort of like pure capitalism and at the very extreme communism.

00:39:34.240 --> 00:39:38.640
[Guest]: And you know, different countries, depending upon the policies they choose at a given point

00:39:38.640 --> 00:39:42.520
[Guest]: of time are actually shifting their position on this.

00:39:42.520 --> 00:39:47.600
[Guest]: And you know, that happens, including China, which started off at the very extreme, but

00:39:47.600 --> 00:39:53.840
[Guest]: now has embraced certain kinds of market reforms, versus, say, United States, which used to

00:39:53.840 --> 00:39:59.080
[Guest]: be a lot more capitalistic at one stage, but increasingly, people think that, for example,

00:39:59.080 --> 00:40:05.040
[Guest]: its entire housing market risk is socialized through the guarantee programs that it has.

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:11.120
[Guest]: It thinks that it has given way to very concentrated power in certain sectors.

00:40:11.120 --> 00:40:17.120
[Guest]: And, you know, maybe there's some forms of crony capitalism also coming in, in some guise

00:40:17.120 --> 00:40:18.120
[Guest]: or the other.

00:40:18.120 --> 00:40:23.160
[Guest]: So, you know, countries are always shifting their positions along the spectrum.

00:40:23.160 --> 00:40:29.240
[Guest]: And then, so that's how, so I don't, so, you know, my view of countries is that each country

00:40:29.240 --> 00:40:30.240
[Guest]: is unique.

00:40:30.240 --> 00:40:37.580
[Guest]: Each country has its own preconditions, which are very important in shaping the ideology

00:40:37.580 --> 00:40:42.600
[Guest]: that the people have, as we were discussing, sometimes this ideology itself needs to be

00:40:42.600 --> 00:40:45.480
[Guest]: shifted or change to happen.

00:40:45.480 --> 00:40:51.880
[Guest]: So the initial conditions are important, because they have left a legacy of ideologies in people's

00:40:51.880 --> 00:40:52.880
[Guest]: minds.

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:57.320
[Guest]: But in some ways, they are also on the spectrum.

00:40:57.320 --> 00:41:05.400
[Guest]: And you can actually think about them, understand them, understand the outcomes, the policy

00:41:05.400 --> 00:41:12.960
[Guest]: choices by actually using economics to understand, then what kind of policies get accepted, when

00:41:12.960 --> 00:41:18.480
[Guest]: is a country more likely to embrace capitalism, when is it more likely to regress towards

00:41:18.480 --> 00:41:25.400
[Guest]: inward looking protectionism, combined with, you know, socialism or at the very extreme

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:28.580
[Guest]: sort of communist kind of policies.

00:41:28.580 --> 00:41:36.440
[Guest]: But the idea that really struck me the most was actually this idea of Austrian economists,

00:41:36.440 --> 00:41:46.520
[Guest]: you know, Hayek most, because he also was very closer to finance, but to an extent also

00:41:46.520 --> 00:41:55.000
[Guest]: von Mises and others, that what too much state control of the factors of production does

00:41:55.000 --> 00:42:03.760
[Guest]: in the end, is that it makes the individual essentially lose his or her entrepreneurial

00:42:03.760 --> 00:42:05.560
[Guest]: spirit.

00:42:05.560 --> 00:42:12.920
[Guest]: Because you know, that even if you are entrepreneurial, there are so many barriers to entry, there

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:19.000
[Guest]: are so many regulations, licensing, etc, to go through.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:23.080
[Guest]: And at an extreme, you're not even allowed because the entire sector may be nationalized,

00:42:23.080 --> 00:42:26.480
[Guest]: and you don't even have private entry that's allowed.

00:42:26.480 --> 00:42:36.240
[Guest]: And that just chokes the individualism, it chokes the entrepreneurial spirit of the individuals.

00:42:36.240 --> 00:42:41.760
[Guest]: And when I read about this, of course, Hayek, you know, in his most, one of his most famous

00:42:41.760 --> 00:42:44.480
[Guest]: books is titled The Road to Serfdom.

00:42:44.480 --> 00:42:49.600
[Guest]: And he's basically saying, you know, you're going to be producing serfs, when you adopt

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:53.840
[Guest]: these kinds of centralized decision making policies.

00:42:53.840 --> 00:43:02.200
[Guest]: And that appealed to me a lot, that over long stretches of time, having too much control

00:43:02.200 --> 00:43:09.800
[Guest]: through the center is ultimately going to kill off entrepreneurship, innovation, enterprise.

00:43:09.800 --> 00:43:16.720
[Guest]: And that became an idea that when you are going through a situation like the Great Depression

00:43:16.720 --> 00:43:24.240
[Guest]: or the Great Recession, you need the state to play an important role to kickstart investments,

00:43:24.240 --> 00:43:30.880
[Guest]: kickstart job creation, you know, give a softer landing to the economy, while it is good,

00:43:30.880 --> 00:43:36.040
[Guest]: it should only be interpreted as something that you should do as a temporary stopgap

00:43:36.040 --> 00:43:38.240
[Guest]: stimulus quick.

00:43:38.240 --> 00:43:44.140
[Guest]: And you know, even, even a short stimulus can go pretty bad, as we know, but at a minimum,

00:43:44.140 --> 00:43:46.840
[Guest]: it has to be seen as a temporary arrangement.

00:43:46.840 --> 00:43:51.220
[Guest]: Because if that becomes the permanent style of the economy, that the government tries

00:43:51.220 --> 00:43:56.680
[Guest]: to do more and more and more, then you will have less and less and less of the private

00:43:56.680 --> 00:43:59.360
[Guest]: sector because their enterprise is actually getting killed.

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:05.120
[Guest]: And actually, in a subtle way, while I'm not so explicit in linking it to the Austrian

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:12.720
[Guest]: economists in my book, that has always been at the back of my mind, that, you know, I

00:44:12.720 --> 00:44:16.800
[Guest]: have these one, there's the Eddie Schroff Memorial Lecture in the book, which is on

00:44:16.800 --> 00:44:19.040
[Guest]: the central bank's independence.

00:44:19.040 --> 00:44:25.040
[Guest]: And then the last speech in the book is actually on how governments crowd out and have focus

00:44:25.040 --> 00:44:26.040
[Guest]: there on finance.

00:44:26.040 --> 00:44:31.800
[Guest]: But when an individual loses the entrepreneurial spirit, that is actually crowding out, because

00:44:31.800 --> 00:44:37.840
[Guest]: that that entrepreneurial spirit has no role in the in a nationalized or very heavily centralized

00:44:37.840 --> 00:44:38.840
[Guest]: economy.

00:44:38.840 --> 00:44:45.120
[Guest]: And to me, this is a key theme of our times right now, in my view, because what has happened

00:44:45.120 --> 00:44:51.720
[Guest]: is the slowdown of global economic growth, especially post the global financial crisis,

00:44:51.720 --> 00:44:59.280
[Guest]: though many would contend this was happening even before in 90s and early 2000s.

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:08.240
[Guest]: But this slowdown has created a chain of events in which more and more is being done by the

00:45:08.240 --> 00:45:09.240
[Guest]: governments.

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:15.400
[Guest]: The government balance sheets the world over are getting bloated, they are spending a lot,

00:45:15.400 --> 00:45:22.440
[Guest]: they are trying to take over significant parts of job creation, subsidies, guarantees, risk

00:45:22.440 --> 00:45:25.760
[Guest]: taking on their balance sheets.

00:45:25.760 --> 00:45:32.040
[Guest]: In fact, many in the United States think that increasingly, most financial sector risks

00:45:32.040 --> 00:45:37.600
[Guest]: are now socialized, whereas the gains remain privatized.

00:45:37.600 --> 00:45:45.440
[Guest]: And what this has done is that I think we really risk the fear, we really risk the prospect

00:45:45.440 --> 00:45:50.560
[Guest]: of and we have to fear that prospect that we lose actually the entrepreneurial spirit

00:45:50.560 --> 00:45:52.720
[Guest]: of the global economy.

00:45:52.720 --> 00:45:58.360
[Guest]: The idea that the best solutions cannot come in the administrative bureaucratic offices

00:45:58.360 --> 00:46:03.280
[Guest]: of the government, where only a small part of the economy sits there, you know, the millions

00:46:03.280 --> 00:46:09.280
[Guest]: are actually out there on the streets, in their homes, they are the ones where the brightest

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:13.720
[Guest]: minds are likely to be for a specific idea.

00:46:13.720 --> 00:46:24.280
[Guest]: And if we don't find a channel for these entrepreneurial ideas to form shape, you know, for them to

00:46:24.280 --> 00:46:30.600
[Guest]: organize themselves as businesses, maybe fail, but fail fast and restart, or many of them

00:46:30.600 --> 00:46:34.280
[Guest]: succeed to becoming the best enterprises going forward.

00:46:34.280 --> 00:46:39.520
[Guest]: I don't see how we can arrest the slide we are seeing in the global growth and productivity.

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:44.200
[Guest]: So at a very deep macro level, I think this is the shift that has happened, it has become

00:46:44.200 --> 00:46:47.360
[Guest]: more pronounced since the global financial crisis.

00:46:47.360 --> 00:46:50.840
[Guest]: My view is that India is also undergoing such a shift.

00:46:50.840 --> 00:46:58.120
[Guest]: We were very nationalized and centralized until the late 80s, then we liberalized, we

00:46:58.120 --> 00:47:03.280
[Guest]: also had a big set of divestment reforms during 98 to 2003.

00:47:03.280 --> 00:47:09.720
[Guest]: But my sense is the policy responses since the global financial crisis are in line with

00:47:09.720 --> 00:47:14.640
[Guest]: the rest of the world in the sense that we have now also moved towards greater and greater

00:47:14.640 --> 00:47:17.380
[Guest]: centralization of the economy.

00:47:17.380 --> 00:47:23.760
[Guest]: What doesn't help us is that our initial conditions feature already a big presence of the state

00:47:23.760 --> 00:47:29.080
[Guest]: in many, many sectors, even non-strategic sectors, we have a big presence of the government

00:47:29.080 --> 00:47:34.400
[Guest]: in the form of public sector banks, public sector owned insurance companies and power

00:47:34.400 --> 00:47:36.640
[Guest]: finance companies, etc.

00:47:36.640 --> 00:47:45.880
[Guest]: So again, on this spectrum, I see India increasingly regressing a bit towards more centrally controlled

00:47:45.880 --> 00:47:50.780
[Guest]: economy and not relinquishing actually the control.

00:47:50.780 --> 00:47:55.800
[Guest]: And the fear I have is that this is going to crowd out the private sector.

00:47:55.800 --> 00:48:01.520
[Guest]: I think, in my view, the reason why private investments in India are not high, it's not

00:48:01.520 --> 00:48:07.800
[Guest]: just because we had a bad loans problem, yes, we did have a very severe bad loans problem

00:48:07.800 --> 00:48:13.160
[Guest]: because of the fiscal stimulus of 9 to 11, 12.

00:48:13.160 --> 00:48:16.720
[Guest]: And you know, those sectors are still not fully back up.

00:48:16.720 --> 00:48:21.720
[Guest]: But I think one big reason why private investments are low is because costs of borrowing are

00:48:21.720 --> 00:48:24.000
[Guest]: very, very high, cost of capital is very high.

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:28.840
[Guest]: And why is the cost of capital very high is because so much of the savings in the economy

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:31.560
[Guest]: are borrowed by the government itself.

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:39.600
[Guest]: And so I would say both as someone who grew up during the nationalized era without any

00:48:39.600 --> 00:48:44.600
[Guest]: clear thinking, but with a lot of questions at the back of your mind, then someone who

00:48:44.600 --> 00:48:49.920
[Guest]: witnessed what used to be a very open capitalist society in the United States.

00:48:49.920 --> 00:48:53.400
[Guest]: And you know, I spent seven years in London between 2008.

00:48:53.400 --> 00:48:56.400
[Guest]: And that was the time I realized that everything is on a spectrum.

00:48:56.400 --> 00:49:01.160
[Guest]: Because when I observed the European economies, I realized it's all on the spectrum.

00:49:01.160 --> 00:49:08.760
[Guest]: But having seen this global experience, I think this is the theme that I would say has

00:49:08.760 --> 00:49:14.120
[Guest]: struck me the most, which is what is the right balance between the government, the private

00:49:14.120 --> 00:49:18.480
[Guest]: sector, the banks and the central bank?

00:49:18.480 --> 00:49:26.320
[Guest]: Can you ensure that all four wheels are moving in tandem and together with no attempt to

00:49:26.320 --> 00:49:29.840
[Guest]: drive the car entirely on just one wheel?

00:49:29.840 --> 00:49:34.280
[Guest]: Because you know, if you do that, there is only so far that your journey will take you.

00:49:34.280 --> 00:49:38.360
[Amit Varma]: So I've just realized that we are not just united in our admiration for Dravid, it's

00:49:38.360 --> 00:49:40.520
[Amit Varma]: also an admiration for Hayek.

00:49:40.520 --> 00:49:44.880
[Amit Varma]: But so I'll digress a bit and I want to spend a lot of time talking about your book and

00:49:44.880 --> 00:49:49.960
[Amit Varma]: your insights in it, of course, but I'll continue digressing a bit and a thought that kind of

00:49:49.960 --> 00:49:55.240
[Amit Varma]: struck me as you were, you know, going through this narrative of how your thinking changed

00:49:55.240 --> 00:50:00.600
[Amit Varma]: and yet, how the world has moved in a certain kind of direction is that it seems to me that

00:50:00.600 --> 00:50:06.040
[Amit Varma]: one of the great battles in our times is not a battle about what ideas work and what ideas

00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:07.040
[Amit Varma]: don't work.

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:11.360
[Amit Varma]: Instead, it is a battle about what narrative sells and what narrative doesn't sell.

00:50:11.360 --> 00:50:16.480
[Amit Varma]: For example, after the 2008 financial crisis, if you ask most people what happened, they

00:50:16.480 --> 00:50:19.400
[Amit Varma]: will say, oh, it's a private sector is greedy bankers.

00:50:19.400 --> 00:50:24.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, as you've spoken about it yourself, you know, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac had a

00:50:24.040 --> 00:50:27.640
[Amit Varma]: big part to play in that the incentives that were there by the government, perhaps you

00:50:27.640 --> 00:50:33.400
[Amit Varma]: can go back to 1977 and talk about the Community Reinvestment Act, a lot of it was the overbearing

00:50:33.400 --> 00:50:38.800
[Amit Varma]: oppressive hand of government, which created those terrible incentives, and led to those

00:50:38.800 --> 00:50:42.520
[Amit Varma]: players behaving in the ways that they did.

00:50:42.520 --> 00:50:47.200
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I've always found it dubious that, you know, when Americans say that, you

00:50:47.200 --> 00:50:51.440
[Amit Varma]: know, losses are being socialized, profits are being privatized, absolutely right.

00:50:51.440 --> 00:50:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, that should not be the case, you create a moral hazard there, you create

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:56.000
[Amit Varma]: the wrong incentives.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:51:00.000
[Amit Varma]: But the broader point is that, despite the fact that everything that's been happening

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:05.920
[Amit Varma]: across the world, all the economic failures, all the political failures that I see, are

00:51:05.920 --> 00:51:10.440
[Amit Varma]: in some way or the other, linked to the role of the state and the incentives that, you

00:51:10.440 --> 00:51:11.640
[Amit Varma]: know, they are setting.

00:51:11.640 --> 00:51:15.720
[Amit Varma]: And yet the dominant narrative is everywhere that it is greedy capitalists, and the state

00:51:15.720 --> 00:51:21.000
[Amit Varma]: is a solution and the state needs to sort of clamp down and instead of Hayek, who is

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:27.200
[Amit Varma]: almost again, a forgotten man today, you have Keynesian ideas, again, taking center stage.

00:51:27.200 --> 00:51:30.760
[Amit Varma]: Is this something that you think about, because on the one hand, you would like to imagine

00:51:30.760 --> 00:51:35.280
[Amit Varma]: that, look, you know, you pick the ideas that work, you go through history, you know, you

00:51:35.280 --> 00:51:39.480
[Amit Varma]: see everything play out, you figure out what works and what doesn't, you go for what works.

00:51:39.480 --> 00:51:45.680
[Amit Varma]: And yet, it's not the idea that works, it's a narrative that sells that is on the ascendant.

00:51:45.680 --> 00:51:46.680
[Guest]: Does this worry you?

00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:47.680
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:51:47.680 --> 00:51:48.680
[Guest]: It worries me a lot.

00:51:48.680 --> 00:51:53.280
[Guest]: And I think, but there's also a challenge in there, as we were discussing earlier, Amit,

00:51:53.280 --> 00:52:01.440
[Guest]: which is that, see, why does the narrative of a Keynesian stimulus or state control during

00:52:01.440 --> 00:52:07.120
[Guest]: a financial crisis or while coming out of a very deep recession work is because actually

00:52:07.120 --> 00:52:12.760
[Guest]: even conceptually, and in theory, there is good rationale for that to be the case.

00:52:12.760 --> 00:52:17.240
[Guest]: Because you know, there is what economists call as a market failure, which is that, you

00:52:17.240 --> 00:52:22.640
[Guest]: know, in a financial crisis, what happens to say one bank is going to have such a bad

00:52:22.640 --> 00:52:29.440
[Guest]: influence all over the system, that or if a large number of firms fail, you know, the

00:52:29.440 --> 00:52:34.000
[Guest]: recession or house foreclosures, they are all going to affect adversely the rest of

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:35.000
[Guest]: the economy.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:38.160
[Guest]: So there is a good theoretical rationale, and it works.

00:52:38.160 --> 00:52:43.600
[Guest]: What is not well appreciated is that, but there are conditions in which this begins

00:52:43.600 --> 00:52:50.160
[Guest]: to start doing harm, because of political capture of the government presence in decision

00:52:50.160 --> 00:52:56.480
[Guest]: making by, say, crony capitalists, second, they could just be outright short termism

00:52:56.480 --> 00:52:58.600
[Guest]: on part of the governments.

00:52:58.600 --> 00:53:03.200
[Guest]: And third, there could be massive crowding out effects, including of the individualism

00:53:03.200 --> 00:53:08.680
[Guest]: and entrepreneurial spirit, leave aside just higher borrowing costs for private sector

00:53:08.680 --> 00:53:10.160
[Guest]: and so on.

00:53:10.160 --> 00:53:16.240
[Guest]: So I think what happens is that it's very appealing to describe these narratives as

00:53:16.240 --> 00:53:17.240
[Guest]: one zero.

00:53:17.240 --> 00:53:23.760
[Guest]: So, you know, you find that individuals are either all entirely pro capitalism, or you

00:53:23.760 --> 00:53:28.960
[Guest]: see individuals who are entirely pro socialism, and you know, everything being done by the

00:53:28.960 --> 00:53:29.960
[Guest]: government.

00:53:29.960 --> 00:53:37.520
[Guest]: But the reality is that what works best is if you are nimble about the state of the world,

00:53:37.520 --> 00:53:43.460
[Guest]: which is based on your economic conditions, how much balance you need to put between these

00:53:43.460 --> 00:53:48.800
[Guest]: two extreme positions, because as we were discussing, clearly, in a financial crisis,

00:53:48.800 --> 00:53:53.440
[Guest]: you need the government to actually backstop and get the system back up.

00:53:53.440 --> 00:54:00.480
[Guest]: But then there should be a graceful unwinding of the extra government imprint that got created.

00:54:00.480 --> 00:54:06.040
[Guest]: Now that second part is always missing whenever the governments are stepping up their positions,

00:54:06.040 --> 00:54:12.720
[Guest]: you know, part of it is, you know, the fact that it's easy to sell a one zero idea than

00:54:12.720 --> 00:54:16.800
[Guest]: to be nuanced and balanced and say, oh, we'll do this now.

00:54:16.800 --> 00:54:22.800
[Guest]: But you know, in three or five years, when things come down, we will, we will withdraw.

00:54:22.800 --> 00:54:28.240
[Guest]: Second very important constraint is that very often, the stimulus decisions are taken by

00:54:28.240 --> 00:54:30.080
[Guest]: one government.

00:54:30.080 --> 00:54:34.960
[Guest]: And even if they were to put in place a decision to withdraw down the line, that is going to

00:54:34.960 --> 00:54:37.440
[Guest]: have to be implemented by another government.

00:54:37.440 --> 00:54:42.200
[Guest]: Now, whatever the first government has announced may not be binding on the second government

00:54:42.200 --> 00:54:43.440
[Guest]: for doing this.

00:54:43.440 --> 00:54:50.200
[Guest]: And you could also get this kind of then possibly a populist trap, which is that once one government

00:54:50.200 --> 00:54:55.160
[Guest]: does this as a stimulus, the other governments want to keep on with it, because it allows

00:54:55.160 --> 00:55:01.240
[Guest]: them to continuously do the short term priming of the economy to show that they will look

00:55:01.240 --> 00:55:02.240
[Guest]: good.

00:55:02.240 --> 00:55:03.720
[Guest]: So but I want to come back to the challenge.

00:55:03.720 --> 00:55:04.720
[Guest]: What is the challenge?

00:55:04.720 --> 00:55:11.000
[Guest]: The challenge to me is that we need to have a more balanced debate about these issues.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:18.240
[Guest]: Whenever the stimulus packages are announced, we need to simultaneously assess their costs.

00:55:18.240 --> 00:55:21.880
[Guest]: We need to think about their long run consequences.

00:55:21.880 --> 00:55:29.620
[Guest]: And we need a lot more discussion, transparency, accountability, in my view, of these packages.

00:55:29.620 --> 00:55:36.320
[Guest]: And conversely, sometimes, when you are too much in what looks like a capitalist society,

00:55:36.320 --> 00:55:43.240
[Guest]: very often, seeds are being sown either for crony capitalism, or for banks and the financial

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:48.360
[Guest]: sectors taking on too much risk, which ultimately, the governments will have to backstop if the

00:55:48.360 --> 00:55:53.020
[Guest]: entire system collapses, because you'll have to protect the depositors in the end.

00:55:53.020 --> 00:55:55.220
[Guest]: And so you also need to guard against that.

00:55:55.220 --> 00:56:00.080
[Guest]: And so it's all about, I think, striking the right balance.

00:56:00.080 --> 00:56:06.640
[Guest]: And you know, giving a balanced perspective is by and large not easy to gain popularity

00:56:06.640 --> 00:56:07.960
[Guest]: with.

00:56:07.960 --> 00:56:13.960
[Guest]: And I think that's where I think so the challenge is that, from a political standpoint, I think

00:56:13.960 --> 00:56:19.960
[Guest]: it is easy to give one zero narratives, because that creates more polarization, and might

00:56:19.960 --> 00:56:24.800
[Guest]: give you enough median voter outcomes that are desirable for you.

00:56:24.800 --> 00:56:32.080
[Guest]: I think the job of the accountants, the think tanks, the economists, the policymakers, the

00:56:32.080 --> 00:56:37.720
[Guest]: independent policymakers, the technocrats, I think their job, in my view, is to continue

00:56:37.720 --> 00:56:43.320
[Guest]: to push the dialogue so that you make it clear, listen, it's not one zero, it's about striking

00:56:43.320 --> 00:56:44.920
[Guest]: the right balance.

00:56:44.920 --> 00:56:50.760
[Guest]: And this balance shifts a little bit in different points of time, based on what kind of situation

00:56:50.760 --> 00:56:55.960
[Guest]: in your banking crisis, yes, the central bank, and the government need to do more.

00:56:55.960 --> 00:57:00.480
[Guest]: But once you move away from that, the role of these two has to diminish.

00:57:00.480 --> 00:57:05.160
[Guest]: And you have to let the private sector flourish again, while recognizing that you don't want

00:57:05.160 --> 00:57:09.080
[Guest]: sort of another full fledged financial crisis again.

00:57:09.080 --> 00:57:14.080
[Guest]: In some ways, actually, this is what financial stability to me is all about.

00:57:14.080 --> 00:57:21.000
[Guest]: It's about allowing the system to flourish privately, while safeguarding that in a stress

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:24.480
[Guest]: scenario, it will have the right levels of resistance.

00:57:24.480 --> 00:57:29.840
[Guest]: And so the if I could just end with an example here, which is the example I like a lot in

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:36.420
[Guest]: thinking about financial stability, and in general, this balance between market friendly

00:57:36.420 --> 00:57:41.840
[Guest]: versus government centered policies is, is really about building a bridge.

00:57:41.840 --> 00:57:49.120
[Guest]: See, I think of financial sector as basically a bridge that carries savings from one shore

00:57:49.120 --> 00:57:53.760
[Guest]: across to borrowers on the other side, you know, the bridge, artery, whatever you want

00:57:53.760 --> 00:57:54.760
[Guest]: to call it.

00:57:54.760 --> 00:57:59.560
[Guest]: Now, how do the engineers approach the construction of the bridges?

00:57:59.560 --> 00:58:02.800
[Guest]: So yeah, there are standards.

00:58:02.800 --> 00:58:03.880
[Guest]: And what are these standards?

00:58:03.880 --> 00:58:08.760
[Guest]: The standards are that you should be able to withstand some fairly high cyclonic hurricane

00:58:08.760 --> 00:58:09.760
[Guest]: kind of winds.

00:58:09.760 --> 00:58:11.720
[Guest]: Now, that is not the normal outcome.

00:58:11.720 --> 00:58:16.320
[Guest]: If you left a private constructor entirely to do this by themselves, they may not put

00:58:16.320 --> 00:58:21.360
[Guest]: in the adequate number of trusses and extra robustness in the bridge.

00:58:21.360 --> 00:58:27.720
[Guest]: But there are some protection or safety standards that ensure that when the situation is going

00:58:27.720 --> 00:58:34.720
[Guest]: to be bad, and you still need the bridge to actually stand there, either to transport

00:58:34.720 --> 00:58:40.040
[Guest]: that time itself or to be available right after the cyclone has gone away.

00:58:40.040 --> 00:58:44.320
[Guest]: You need that robustness investment to be made ahead of time.

00:58:44.320 --> 00:58:49.640
[Guest]: And my sense is that if we took this approach, which is that we let the system function most

00:58:49.640 --> 00:58:57.160
[Guest]: of the time, with the individual's entrepreneurial spirit, but we create defenses, so that when

00:58:57.160 --> 00:59:02.840
[Guest]: things go bad, the mop up by the governments, the central banks, etc, doesn't have to be

00:59:02.840 --> 00:59:08.080
[Guest]: heavy handed, because you've already built so much robustness in the system, that it's

00:59:08.080 --> 00:59:12.560
[Guest]: only in the very extreme wind conditions that the bridge might collapse, then of course,

00:59:12.560 --> 00:59:17.160
[Guest]: you need to reconstruct, or that you will have to do minimal repairs, because actually

00:59:17.160 --> 00:59:19.160
[Guest]: your bridge was so strong to start with.

00:59:19.160 --> 00:59:23.000
[Guest]: I think this is the shift in mindset that is required.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:25.080
[Guest]: It requires thinking long term.

00:59:25.080 --> 00:59:30.360
[Guest]: It requires entertaining stress scenarios that are not your present day challenge.

00:59:30.360 --> 00:59:36.240
[Guest]: And it requires making some sacrifices, you're going to have to increase the cost of production

00:59:36.240 --> 00:59:37.240
[Guest]: of the bridge.

00:59:37.240 --> 00:59:41.480
[Guest]: It cannot be built as quickly as you thought would be built otherwise.

00:59:41.480 --> 00:59:48.480
[Guest]: But I very much see the role of the economists, think tanks, policy makers, analysts as so

00:59:48.480 --> 00:59:54.760
[Guest]: important in the current times, when everyone is going for one zero narratives, that we

00:59:54.760 --> 01:00:00.280
[Guest]: need to bring the discussion towards it being about a better balance.

01:00:00.280 --> 01:00:04.880
[Guest]: And one that is based on the conditions and the needs of the economy at a given point

01:00:04.880 --> 01:00:10.120
[Guest]: of time, without disregarding what will be the consequences of the policies you adopt

01:00:10.120 --> 01:00:11.120
[Guest]: now down the line.

01:00:11.120 --> 01:00:15.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'm loving your metaphors in this episode, the heart and the arteries of bridge.

01:00:15.480 --> 01:00:19.760
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I thought, you know, when you said that, you know, you had one way of explaining

01:00:19.760 --> 01:00:23.160
[Amit Varma]: this, I thought you're going to talk about Dravid's innings in that famous test in Headingley,

01:00:23.160 --> 01:00:27.760
[Amit Varma]: where he saw out the new ball and made that phenomenal hundred on day one, partly with

01:00:27.760 --> 01:00:31.760
[Amit Varma]: Sanjay Bangar and then the next day, Tendulkar and Ganguly made big hundreds.

01:00:31.760 --> 01:00:34.920
[Amit Varma]: And if you just look at the scorecard, it's like, okay, they all made hundreds, what's

01:00:34.920 --> 01:00:35.920
[Amit Varma]: a big deal.

01:00:35.920 --> 01:00:39.880
[Amit Varma]: But Dravid sort of weathered the storm and then the other guys thrived.

01:00:39.880 --> 01:00:43.880
[Amit Varma]: So with a bridge, I would say that for me, where that analogy kinds of falls apart is

01:00:43.880 --> 01:00:48.800
[Amit Varma]: that this particular bridge that you're talking about has so many moving parts, and all of

01:00:48.800 --> 01:00:52.720
[Amit Varma]: them have their own incentives that it's just incredibly complex.

01:00:52.720 --> 01:00:55.280
[Amit Varma]: I guess no metaphor is perfect.

01:00:55.280 --> 01:01:00.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, before we, you know, get to the book and the, you know, the meat of our discussion

01:01:00.440 --> 01:01:03.960
[Amit Varma]: today, a final digressive question, which again, comes from an aside in your book, I

01:01:03.960 --> 01:01:07.760
[Amit Varma]: think, and also something you said a while back, where you were talking about your personal

01:01:07.760 --> 01:01:12.920
[Amit Varma]: journey, and you pointed out how countries are sort of placed along this continuum.

01:01:12.920 --> 01:01:18.560
[Amit Varma]: And where a country is on the continuum can often shape how its people think about the

01:01:18.560 --> 01:01:20.360
[Amit Varma]: world and their worldviews.

01:01:20.360 --> 01:01:26.240
[Amit Varma]: And one sort of, you know, thought that I've been sort of toying with for a long, long

01:01:26.240 --> 01:01:32.040
[Amit Varma]: time is how institutions can shape a culture in very deep ways, like Jagdish Bhagwati had

01:01:32.040 --> 01:01:36.840
[Amit Varma]: once, you know, I think in the year 2000, contrasted China and India and pointed out

01:01:36.840 --> 01:01:41.480
[Amit Varma]: that look, China is profit seeking, India is rent seeking, there's a rent seeking mentality.

01:01:41.480 --> 01:01:45.080
[Amit Varma]: People don't think of how can I serve the other person and make some profit, they think

01:01:45.080 --> 01:01:49.400
[Amit Varma]: about how can I exploit the person, how can I, you know, exploit the situation.

01:01:49.400 --> 01:01:55.580
[Amit Varma]: And my sense of why that is, and you know, it's a speculation, is that it is partly because

01:01:55.580 --> 01:02:00.440
[Amit Varma]: of our institutions, because of the way our government was set up over the last seven

01:02:00.440 --> 01:02:06.320
[Amit Varma]: decades since independence that we are essentially a rent seeking society, the role of the state

01:02:06.320 --> 01:02:10.480
[Amit Varma]: for much of this time has been vastly oversized.

01:02:10.480 --> 01:02:14.320
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the incentives for a person would always be that be part of the state

01:02:14.320 --> 01:02:18.920
[Amit Varma]: be part of that entity that has a monopoly on violence and so much discretion.

01:02:18.920 --> 01:02:20.640
[Amit Varma]: And that's where you'll make the money.

01:02:20.640 --> 01:02:24.240
[Amit Varma]: And you know, within the book somewhere, again, I didn't mark that passage, so I don't remember

01:02:24.240 --> 01:02:28.560
[Amit Varma]: the exact words, but you've similarly spoken about how the structures within the financial

01:02:28.560 --> 01:02:34.880
[Amit Varma]: system can shape the culture and the attitudes of, you know, the players involved.

01:02:34.880 --> 01:02:36.760
[Guest]: What are your sort of thoughts on this?

01:02:36.760 --> 01:02:44.440
[Guest]: Yeah, I'm, I'm very much a fan of this view, both parts of your question, one that it is

01:02:44.440 --> 01:02:51.200
[Guest]: about institutions in the end, that the long term outcomes of the country, I'm a big, I

01:02:51.200 --> 01:02:58.640
[Guest]: think I'm convinced by the research of Simoglu, Robinson, Fukuyama, and others that, you know,

01:02:58.640 --> 01:03:03.080
[Guest]: in the end, countries that become like Denmark in their quality of living over a period of

01:03:03.080 --> 01:03:09.360
[Guest]: time, and are able to offer that standard of living to its citizenry are countries where

01:03:09.360 --> 01:03:16.240
[Guest]: institutions such as the rule of law, enforcement of contracts, sanctity of the elections, etc,

01:03:16.240 --> 01:03:17.240
[Guest]: are in good shape.

01:03:17.240 --> 01:03:22.360
[Guest]: In fact, in the A.D. Shroff Memorial Lecture, I, my attempt was to say that even a central

01:03:22.360 --> 01:03:29.520
[Guest]: bank should actually be viewed as on the same pedestal as all these other institutions in

01:03:29.520 --> 01:03:30.520
[Guest]: a democracy.

01:03:30.520 --> 01:03:35.960
[Guest]: It's an important part of checks and balances, just the way we would not want the Judiciary

01:03:35.960 --> 01:03:43.240
[Guest]: or the Election Commission to be compromised in a democracy, we should also not want that,

01:03:43.240 --> 01:03:48.840
[Guest]: you know, the central bank is actually compromised in its decision making just for the short

01:03:48.840 --> 01:03:54.120
[Guest]: term populist gains of the ruling day government's environment, because that will keep the financial

01:03:54.120 --> 01:03:58.760
[Guest]: sector policies anchored towards the long term stability.

01:03:58.760 --> 01:04:09.120
[Guest]: Now, turning that around, why is an institution of weak regulation or central banking a problem?

01:04:09.120 --> 01:04:13.400
[Guest]: It is a problem exactly for the reasons you mentioned, because when the presence of the

01:04:13.400 --> 01:04:18.240
[Guest]: state is large in the financial sector, so there are public sector banks, there's tremendous

01:04:18.240 --> 01:04:24.880
[Guest]: presence in insurance, pension, non-bank finance, etc, so you know, they are all around, then

01:04:24.880 --> 01:04:31.760
[Guest]: there is a constant tendency to lean on the central bank to make it easier for these entities

01:04:31.760 --> 01:04:35.000
[Guest]: to survive in spite of their performance.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:40.800
[Guest]: There is also a constant pressure on the central bank to change the rules of the game, not

01:04:40.800 --> 01:04:45.040
[Guest]: just central bank, I would say even other financial regulators, such as securities markets

01:04:45.040 --> 01:04:51.520
[Guest]: regulator, insurance regulator, pension regulator, so that all of these public sector entities

01:04:51.520 --> 01:04:57.320
[Guest]: in the financial sector, they are essentially all supporting the government's balance sheet

01:04:57.320 --> 01:05:02.400
[Guest]: to be large, allowing their programs to be larger by channeling the savings that are

01:05:02.400 --> 01:05:09.680
[Guest]: going from depositors, insurance premium payers, pensioners, etc, in one way or the other,

01:05:09.680 --> 01:05:13.680
[Guest]: make it cheaper for the government to get its hands on to the savings compared to the

01:05:13.680 --> 01:05:14.680
[Guest]: private sector.

01:05:14.680 --> 01:05:20.520
[Guest]: Now, once the private sector is crowded out, they have a higher cost of borrowing, in general,

01:05:20.520 --> 01:05:25.720
[Guest]: higher cost of capital, so they have to economize somewhere else, they can't compete that easily

01:05:25.720 --> 01:05:30.600
[Guest]: because actually they have to generate high returns because their cost of capital is very

01:05:30.600 --> 01:05:31.600
[Guest]: high.

01:05:31.600 --> 01:05:33.800
[Guest]: So, they start looking for corners.

01:05:33.800 --> 01:05:40.000
[Guest]: In my view, this could be one of the reasons why the overall evasion culture builds up

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:44.460
[Guest]: in the country because you've actually, by state being so large, you are subjecting them

01:05:44.460 --> 01:05:49.840
[Guest]: to such high required returns on their investments that they say, I have to figure out how to

01:05:49.840 --> 01:05:54.960
[Guest]: optimize my taxes in a very, very massive way in order to generate some return to those

01:05:54.960 --> 01:05:57.160
[Guest]: who are providing me capital.

01:05:57.160 --> 01:05:58.160
[Guest]: That's one.

01:05:58.160 --> 01:06:03.640
[Guest]: And then, they know that the state is present everywhere, not just in financial sector,

01:06:03.640 --> 01:06:06.040
[Guest]: but even in some non-financial sector.

01:06:06.040 --> 01:06:10.820
[Guest]: Very often in countries where government is large, it is a reflection of this ideology

01:06:10.820 --> 01:06:16.000
[Guest]: as we discussed, and they also start wanting to have to control decisions rather than making

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:23.000
[Guest]: it like a seamless processing of licensing and granting of permissions, etc.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:29.960
[Guest]: And then, you end up having to work with the government, so to speak, even the tech sector

01:06:29.960 --> 01:06:36.200
[Guest]: firms in the country, my friends who are entrepreneurs, they tell me that they can't arrange physical

01:06:36.200 --> 01:06:42.280
[Guest]: space for their offices without actually doing some gafla on the side with the municipalities

01:06:42.280 --> 01:06:48.280
[Guest]: or whatever to get the land or get access to the property and so on.

01:06:48.280 --> 01:06:55.120
[Guest]: And then third, because you know that the state wants to be so large, you know that

01:06:55.120 --> 01:06:59.000
[Guest]: there will be frequent interactions.

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:04.080
[Guest]: And if you can just work with them to get a few decisions your way, maybe this could

01:07:04.080 --> 01:07:10.760
[Guest]: be a very symbiotic relationship for that enterprise and the government, not necessarily

01:07:10.760 --> 01:07:14.080
[Guest]: always to the benefit of the economy.

01:07:14.080 --> 01:07:21.000
[Guest]: And you get this sort of hyperactive consultations, lobbying, crony capitalism, etc., find a route.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:27.640
[Guest]: And I'm fully with Professor Bhagwati here, which is that the biggest corruption of the

01:07:27.640 --> 01:07:35.200
[Guest]: society, because of the strong presence of the state, comes because it ultimately shifts

01:07:35.200 --> 01:07:43.920
[Guest]: the focus away from value creation, entrepreneurship, and enterprise to rent-seeking, tax evasion

01:07:43.920 --> 01:07:50.240
[Guest]: and essentially, you know, getting concessions from the government, which are out of line.

01:07:50.240 --> 01:07:57.880
[Guest]: I saw that culture when I was in India, I felt that many of our banks, financial firms

01:07:57.880 --> 01:08:04.560
[Guest]: and industrialists, they are spending so much time interacting with the government offices,

01:08:04.560 --> 01:08:11.240
[Guest]: rather than actually focusing on their core businesses, thinking hard about their strategies,

01:08:11.240 --> 01:08:14.180
[Guest]: etc., that it seemed like a complete waste.

01:08:14.180 --> 01:08:19.480
[Guest]: And this is the, going back to the Hayekian, Austrian thought of crowding out, I think

01:08:19.480 --> 01:08:24.840
[Guest]: this is a very subtle form of crowding out of the economy's productivity.

01:08:24.840 --> 01:08:26.800
[Guest]: And this is the fear that I have.

01:08:26.800 --> 01:08:32.720
[Guest]: My fear is that as the state, we already have a large state, so to speak, in terms of its

01:08:32.720 --> 01:08:39.080
[Guest]: presence in several sectors, in terms of its debt to GDP ratio, in terms of the fiscal

01:08:39.080 --> 01:08:44.280
[Guest]: deficit amount that they have to borrow every year to meet their needs of their various

01:08:44.280 --> 01:08:45.280
[Guest]: expenditures.

01:08:45.280 --> 01:08:46.280
[Guest]: It's already very large.

01:08:46.280 --> 01:08:53.960
[Guest]: If we don't reverse track, we really have to entertain the scenario of lost productivity,

01:08:53.960 --> 01:08:56.720
[Guest]: crowding out of enterprise.

01:08:56.720 --> 01:09:01.120
[Guest]: And you know, this will cost us in the long run.

01:09:01.120 --> 01:09:08.960
[Guest]: So I think, as I was saying, without having referred to the Austrian economists very directly,

01:09:08.960 --> 01:09:12.840
[Guest]: this is actually a deeper undercurrent of the book.

01:09:12.840 --> 01:09:21.400
[Guest]: And in fact, in my India book on government-sponsored enterprises in the United States, so we were

01:09:21.400 --> 01:09:25.760
[Guest]: explaining the role played by Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac in the mortgage debacle in the

01:09:25.760 --> 01:09:26.760
[Guest]: United States.

01:09:26.760 --> 01:09:30.920
[Guest]: I had an India version of the book, the book was called Guaranteed to Fail.

01:09:30.920 --> 01:09:36.040
[Guest]: In the India version, I had a chapter on India as to, you know, what are the lessons for

01:09:36.040 --> 01:09:42.720
[Guest]: India from the failures of mortgages and Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac in the United States.

01:09:42.720 --> 01:09:49.600
[Guest]: And you know, there's a six-word proverb in Gujarati, you know, coming down from centuries,

01:09:49.600 --> 01:09:54.360
[Guest]: I guess, which I think has taught me more economics than anything else.

01:09:54.360 --> 01:10:00.160
[Guest]: And it goes as, jya raja vyapari, ya praja bhikari.

01:10:00.160 --> 01:10:07.960
[Guest]: And you know, it's such a deep saying, whoever wrote this is, in my mind, one of the greatest

01:10:07.960 --> 01:10:12.560
[Guest]: economists to have ever existed on the terra firma.

01:10:12.560 --> 01:10:18.480
[Guest]: And it is so deep because there are so many shades to how this becomes true.

01:10:18.480 --> 01:10:25.720
[Guest]: That when the government or the king is trying to be a trader and be in the business itself,

01:10:25.720 --> 01:10:31.960
[Guest]: ultimately, you end up with people in poverty and being beggars.

01:10:31.960 --> 01:10:36.840
[Guest]: And there are so many channels through which this arises and it does, I have found it so

01:10:36.840 --> 01:10:37.840
[Guest]: thought provoking.

01:10:37.840 --> 01:10:42.160
[Guest]: By the way, this was also taught to me by my teacher, Shailesh Shastri, who I mentioned,

01:10:42.160 --> 01:10:44.280
[Guest]: he was the one who told me this.

01:10:44.280 --> 01:10:49.400
[Guest]: Of course, as a student, I had no understanding as to how deep this message is.

01:10:49.400 --> 01:10:53.280
[Guest]: You got some idea, you know, in Amar Chitra Ghata, there were these kings and, you know,

01:10:53.280 --> 01:10:56.560
[Guest]: they were not ruling their citizens very well.

01:10:56.560 --> 01:11:01.440
[Guest]: But it was only when I started doing economics that I realized, oh, there was such a wealth

01:11:01.440 --> 01:11:05.680
[Guest]: of wisdom and knowledge in this.

01:11:05.680 --> 01:11:10.680
[Guest]: And I think that we have to worry about this outcome.

01:11:10.680 --> 01:11:14.340
[Guest]: And in the book, I tried to explain this in the previous chapter, if I could just finish

01:11:14.340 --> 01:11:19.720
[Guest]: with that thought, which is that, you know, I refer to this concept of fiscal dominance,

01:11:19.720 --> 01:11:23.960
[Guest]: which is that the government is becoming too overbearing in its control over financial

01:11:23.960 --> 01:11:24.960
[Guest]: sector policies.

01:11:24.960 --> 01:11:29.400
[Guest]: And it's important to understand why this is shifting over time.

01:11:29.400 --> 01:11:34.280
[Guest]: Because I think, if you don't understand these shifts over time, you will not understand

01:11:34.280 --> 01:11:38.840
[Guest]: what are the root causes of the problem, you will not get the diagnosis right.

01:11:38.840 --> 01:11:43.720
[Guest]: I think the shift is happening because we were first a nationalized country.

01:11:43.720 --> 01:11:48.560
[Guest]: So, you know, in 70s and 80s, it didn't matter if you controlled the financial sector via

01:11:48.560 --> 01:11:53.880
[Guest]: the government, because there was no private sector to speak of for all practical purposes.

01:11:53.880 --> 01:11:59.960
[Guest]: Then we liberalized, because we had no choice, we failed as a centralized nation, we were

01:11:59.960 --> 01:12:04.160
[Guest]: at IMF, and you know, they required us to undergo structural packages.

01:12:04.160 --> 01:12:08.560
[Guest]: So then we, you know, there was a coincidence of politics and economics, we got the right

01:12:08.560 --> 01:12:10.280
[Guest]: changes through.

01:12:10.280 --> 01:12:16.320
[Guest]: And for about 16-17 years, we were good with that also, the global growth was good and

01:12:16.320 --> 01:12:17.320
[Guest]: so on.

01:12:17.320 --> 01:12:22.400
[Guest]: But in this global financial crisis, global growth slowed down.

01:12:22.400 --> 01:12:28.320
[Guest]: And we had already reaped some of the low hanging fruits of the 90s reforms.

01:12:28.320 --> 01:12:31.280
[Guest]: And now we needed actually a next set.

01:12:31.280 --> 01:12:34.160
[Guest]: And I think this is where we stumbled.

01:12:34.160 --> 01:12:40.800
[Guest]: For the next 10-12 years, instead of actually moving the economy towards a more liberalized

01:12:40.800 --> 01:12:48.400
[Guest]: state, more undertaking greater divestments of the governments where it had not yet divested,

01:12:48.400 --> 01:12:52.320
[Guest]: we have adopted, I would say, a hodgepodge of policies.

01:12:52.320 --> 01:12:57.800
[Guest]: Some have tended to liberalize, but many have also regressed in terms of increasing the

01:12:57.800 --> 01:12:58.800
[Guest]: state control.

01:12:58.800 --> 01:13:04.760
[Guest]: There have been attempts to directly control the financial sector outcomes through bank

01:13:04.760 --> 01:13:09.880
[Guest]: lending decisions, attempts to control the central bank policies, etc.

01:13:09.880 --> 01:13:16.360
[Guest]: And I think it is because of these growth slowdown, the demand in the narrative for

01:13:16.360 --> 01:13:21.680
[Guest]: the government to start playing a bigger role, governments approaching it myopically, rather

01:13:21.680 --> 01:13:27.760
[Guest]: than factoring in the long run costs of excessive state control, that we are now seeing a gradual

01:13:27.760 --> 01:13:31.520
[Guest]: shift over 10-12 years in this direction.

01:13:31.520 --> 01:13:39.160
[Guest]: Part of the book is written because I want us to reconsider whether this shift that we

01:13:39.160 --> 01:13:48.080
[Guest]: are experiencing, away from our liberalization divestment paradigm of 90s, back towards centralization

01:13:48.080 --> 01:13:52.200
[Guest]: and more control of policies and regulations.

01:13:52.200 --> 01:13:54.200
[Guest]: Is this really what we want to do?

01:13:54.200 --> 01:13:58.240
[Guest]: We want to go back to the 70s and 80s-style India?

01:13:58.240 --> 01:14:05.640
[Guest]: The fear is that we end up with the same levels of rate of growth, rather than actually realizing

01:14:05.640 --> 01:14:12.680
[Guest]: the 8-9% that our kind of demographics and youth aspirations command and demand.

01:14:12.680 --> 01:14:16.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, despite the fact that you sometimes say that there is a bird of optimism within

01:14:16.920 --> 01:14:20.280
[Amit Varma]: you, that's a pretty sort of worrying note.

01:14:20.280 --> 01:14:23.760
[Amit Varma]: You know, while you were sort of speaking, I remembered an episode I'd done with a friend

01:14:23.760 --> 01:14:27.700
[Amit Varma]: of mine on restaurant regulations, and he was a restauranteur, which perfectly illustrates

01:14:27.700 --> 01:14:31.600
[Amit Varma]: what you said about the role of the state, where he pointed out that when he ran a restaurant

01:14:31.600 --> 01:14:36.560
[Amit Varma]: and he used to run one in Bangalore, that he realized that there were two conflicting

01:14:36.560 --> 01:14:37.560
[Amit Varma]: regulations.

01:14:37.560 --> 01:14:41.240
[Amit Varma]: The excise department, because they wanted to monitor the alcohol that was going into

01:14:41.240 --> 01:14:45.200
[Amit Varma]: the restaurant, insisted that there be only one entry into the restaurant.

01:14:45.200 --> 01:14:50.480
[Amit Varma]: And the fire department, for safety reasons, insisted that there be multiple doors.

01:14:50.480 --> 01:14:53.280
[Amit Varma]: So the poor guy, no matter what he does, he's breaking the law.

01:14:53.280 --> 01:14:56.840
[Amit Varma]: And he's giving out at least one bribe every month, possibly two.

01:14:56.840 --> 01:15:00.120
[Amit Varma]: And you know, other businessmen have told me that they give up to 30-40 bribes a month.

01:15:00.120 --> 01:15:04.400
[Amit Varma]: It's almost like you keep one person just for sort of dealing with bribes and doing

01:15:04.400 --> 01:15:05.400
[Amit Varma]: all of that.

01:15:05.400 --> 01:15:08.720
[Amit Varma]: And you've got a great illustration of how this kind of thinking can seep into the culture

01:15:08.720 --> 01:15:12.800
[Amit Varma]: in your book, where, you know, you've pointed out at one point that you've spoken about

01:15:12.800 --> 01:15:16.680
[Amit Varma]: the tech industry and the pharma industry and said, look at the entrepreneurial spirit.

01:15:16.680 --> 01:15:19.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's because they're relatively lightly regulated.

01:15:19.920 --> 01:15:24.160
[Amit Varma]: But you said as far as a brick and mortar industries are concerned, you used to have

01:15:24.160 --> 01:15:30.160
[Amit Varma]: a file called, Allah ke naam pe de de baba, because they would most often be writing,

01:15:30.160 --> 01:15:35.880
[Amit Varma]: asking for, you know, restructuring bad loans or evergreening bad loans and so on and so

01:15:35.880 --> 01:15:36.880
[Amit Varma]: forth.

01:15:36.880 --> 01:15:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And would that be an example of how the culture can shift?

01:15:39.880 --> 01:15:43.760
[Amit Varma]: Because then if there are industries which are structurally like that, then that will

01:15:43.760 --> 01:15:48.400
[Amit Varma]: attract a certain kind of person and repel another kind of person and they're exactly

01:15:48.400 --> 01:15:49.400
[Amit Varma]: the wrong outcomes.

01:15:49.400 --> 01:15:50.400
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:15:50.400 --> 01:15:55.200
[Guest]: In fact, at my farewell speech at the Reserve Bank of India, this is exactly what I said.

01:15:55.200 --> 01:16:00.880
[Guest]: I didn't describe our quest as necessarily one of just restoring financial stability.

01:16:00.880 --> 01:16:08.960
[Guest]: I described the quest as one of trying to convert the India businesses from a rent extraction

01:16:08.960 --> 01:16:14.400
[Guest]: society towards more of a value creation society, which is, you know, we need to shift the thinking

01:16:14.400 --> 01:16:21.760
[Guest]: where the way you generate value is not by gold plating and getting your loan gold plated

01:16:21.760 --> 01:16:26.560
[Guest]: and then over borrowing and then defaulting and then siphoning of the fund somewhere.

01:16:26.560 --> 01:16:31.280
[Guest]: The way you create value is by actually genuinely designing new products, setting up thriving

01:16:31.280 --> 01:16:37.520
[Guest]: enterprises for the long run, repaying the loans and the borrowings you have undertaken,

01:16:37.520 --> 01:16:42.000
[Guest]: and yet be creating a lot of value for yourself and for the society as a whole.

01:16:42.000 --> 01:16:47.480
[Guest]: Because when you create value, you are solving some genuine economic problem on the ground

01:16:47.480 --> 01:16:49.440
[Guest]: for the citizens.

01:16:49.440 --> 01:16:54.080
[Guest]: And I think we need a very significant shift in this culture.

01:16:54.080 --> 01:16:59.120
[Guest]: It is a very complex problem because it is partly because of the overarching presence

01:16:59.120 --> 01:17:07.000
[Guest]: of the state, both in certain sectors as well as in the financial sector, that has prevented

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:14.640
[Guest]: actually laying down a set of rules through which risk taking is supported.

01:17:14.640 --> 01:17:20.560
[Guest]: But it is with the right due diligence, monitoring and collection skills, especially at our public

01:17:20.560 --> 01:17:22.200
[Guest]: sector banks.

01:17:22.200 --> 01:17:23.960
[Guest]: And to do that, why is that?

01:17:23.960 --> 01:17:29.320
[Guest]: Because if you want the banks to lend well, then it has to be the case that when they

01:17:29.320 --> 01:17:34.960
[Guest]: don't lend well, there have to be consequences, because that has got to be the most important

01:17:34.960 --> 01:17:37.960
[Guest]: disciplining factor on these banks.

01:17:37.960 --> 01:17:43.320
[Guest]: Now, what has happened with public sector banks is that neither is there any significant

01:17:43.320 --> 01:17:48.360
[Guest]: penalty for not lending well, because there is the support of the state implicitly in

01:17:48.360 --> 01:17:50.200
[Guest]: one form or the other.

01:17:50.200 --> 01:17:57.160
[Guest]: And the bank regulation has been compromised again and again and again, so that the government,

01:17:57.160 --> 01:18:02.200
[Guest]: which is the ultimate principal shareholder, also doesn't have to bear immediate consequences

01:18:02.200 --> 01:18:06.240
[Guest]: of actually chipping in capital to these banks that have not done well.

01:18:06.240 --> 01:18:13.240
[Guest]: Now, the sum total of all this is that public sector banks have become a quote unquote vehicle

01:18:13.240 --> 01:18:19.080
[Guest]: through which the rent extraction by the brick and mortar industries has taken place in the

01:18:19.080 --> 01:18:20.080
[Guest]: country.

01:18:20.080 --> 01:18:24.680
[Guest]: Now, it need not just be at the brick and mortar industry level.

01:18:24.680 --> 01:18:29.240
[Guest]: Suppose you keep encouraging public sector banks to lend to micro, small and medium sized

01:18:29.240 --> 01:18:34.120
[Guest]: enterprises or to make the mudra loans, but these are not made well.

01:18:34.120 --> 01:18:38.880
[Guest]: Then once again, the taxpayers as a whole are simply doing a transfer to one segment

01:18:38.880 --> 01:18:44.000
[Guest]: of the society which is getting freebies without actually having the capacity to repay these

01:18:44.000 --> 01:18:45.000
[Guest]: loans.

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:55.200
[Guest]: So, I think we are in need of a very fundamental reshift of the financial sector regulation,

01:18:55.200 --> 01:19:01.480
[Guest]: so that those who bear the risks are made to pay for them.

01:19:01.480 --> 01:19:06.480
[Guest]: And only if you make them pay for these risks, will they actually make the right decision

01:19:06.480 --> 01:19:09.280
[Guest]: to allocate capital judiciously.

01:19:09.280 --> 01:19:15.300
[Guest]: Once capital is being allocated judiciously, businesses will have no choice but to actually

01:19:15.300 --> 01:19:18.880
[Guest]: go and come up with better value propositions.

01:19:18.880 --> 01:19:23.920
[Guest]: And once they have better value propositions, we will get more enterprise, more thriving

01:19:23.920 --> 01:19:29.600
[Guest]: environments, more employment in these traditional sectors, which do not seem to be exactly as

01:19:29.600 --> 01:19:33.760
[Guest]: you said, doing as well as our tech and pharma sector.

01:19:33.760 --> 01:19:38.520
[Guest]: And I think it is a great example because see, tech and pharma is not that reliant on

01:19:38.520 --> 01:19:39.520
[Guest]: bank finance.

01:19:39.520 --> 01:19:47.800
[Guest]: They are very heavily reliant either on market finance or actually on just equity investments.

01:19:47.800 --> 01:19:52.480
[Guest]: And you know, a lot of it is actually in the form of foreign direct investments from abroad.

01:19:52.480 --> 01:19:56.120
[Guest]: And just look at the number of unicorns we are creating in the tech space.

01:19:56.120 --> 01:19:58.400
[Guest]: It's very, very impressive.

01:19:58.400 --> 01:20:03.520
[Guest]: And you can see the shift when we came out of IIT Bombay in 95, we didn't have so much

01:20:03.520 --> 01:20:07.320
[Guest]: entrepreneurship in us, because there was nothing happening that much on the ground.

01:20:07.320 --> 01:20:11.480
[Guest]: It was still the beginning of the tech era in India.

01:20:11.480 --> 01:20:16.440
[Guest]: You go to an IIT now and you look at the entrepreneurship in the youth, they all want to set up their

01:20:16.440 --> 01:20:17.440
[Guest]: own businesses.

01:20:17.440 --> 01:20:18.440
[Guest]: Why?

01:20:18.440 --> 01:20:21.560
[Guest]: Because they see that it can be done on ground.

01:20:21.560 --> 01:20:28.680
[Guest]: And you know, somehow, fortunately, at least in the tech space, we have not overregulated

01:20:28.680 --> 01:20:29.840
[Guest]: the space.

01:20:29.840 --> 01:20:31.360
[Guest]: It's managing to do well.

01:20:31.360 --> 01:20:36.440
[Guest]: There is one criticism that it hasn't created as much products of its own.

01:20:36.440 --> 01:20:41.760
[Guest]: But I think now gradually through the sharing economy, maybe even that is changing a little

01:20:41.760 --> 01:20:42.760
[Guest]: bit.

01:20:42.760 --> 01:20:48.120
[Guest]: I think maybe the newer apps which are getting developed in India, they are more to serve

01:20:48.120 --> 01:20:54.720
[Guest]: the local needs of the Indians rather than just to be the outsourcing office of the rest

01:20:54.720 --> 01:20:55.720
[Guest]: of the world.

01:20:55.720 --> 01:21:01.720
[Guest]: So I think that's a good contrast we observe between brick and mortar and the tech space.

01:21:01.720 --> 01:21:07.400
[Guest]: And I hope that we can really fix the bank lending in a significant way.

01:21:07.400 --> 01:21:12.880
[Guest]: And that's why Dr. Raghuram Rajan and I, we have actually just released a piece last week,

01:21:12.880 --> 01:21:18.880
[Guest]: Indian banks, a time to reform where we are actually laying out a full blueprint of also

01:21:18.880 --> 01:21:24.080
[Guest]: how to improve the lending decisions, the monitoring, the providing for the risks, especially

01:21:24.080 --> 01:21:29.160
[Guest]: at the public sector banks, and how over a period of time to improve their governance

01:21:29.160 --> 01:21:31.240
[Guest]: and change their ownership structure.

01:21:31.240 --> 01:21:32.600
[Amit Varma]: That's quite insightful and wonderful.

01:21:32.600 --> 01:21:33.760
[Amit Varma]: Let's take a quick commercial break.

01:21:33.760 --> 01:21:37.680
[Amit Varma]: And once we come back to it, I promise our listeners that we'll get to the meat of the

01:21:37.680 --> 01:21:43.760
[Amit Varma]: matter, which is, you know, firstly, Dr. Acharya's experiences in the Reserve Bank of India and

01:21:43.760 --> 01:21:49.560
[Amit Varma]: then the whole notion of fiscal dominance, which he calls a theory of everything in India,

01:21:49.560 --> 01:21:52.080
[Amit Varma]: which I found very convincing and couldn't agree more with.

01:21:52.080 --> 01:21:56.400
[Amit Varma]: So after a brief commercial break.

01:21:56.400 --> 01:21:59.960
[Amit Varma]: On the scene and the unseen, I often speak about positive sum games.

01:21:59.960 --> 01:22:04.960
[Amit Varma]: Well, if you want to be surrounded by beauty, and you love fine art, I have a win win proposition

01:22:04.960 --> 01:22:05.960
[Amit Varma]: for you.

01:22:05.960 --> 01:22:08.400
[Amit Varma]: Head on over to Indiancolors.com.

01:22:08.400 --> 01:22:13.840
[Amit Varma]: Indiancolors licenses images of fine art from some of the best contemporary artists in India

